s0_-B_TKzgQ.title: WORLD’S HOTTEST CITY (140 Degrees!!)
s0_-B_TKzgQ.description:
Secure your "Link by JUST GO" Bracelet Here! https://forms.gle/xpcZQc5LokXpxEJK6
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

Welcome to Jahra, Kuwait - the city with the hottest ever recorded temperature on earth! 

I went to Kuwait a few months ago, on the exact hottest day of the year, so I could see what life is like in the brutal heat!! How on earth can people survive and do their daily activities when it’s 55 degrees Celsius, or 140 degrees Fahrenheit outside? How can they eat? Sleep? Pray? Enjoy life? 

I met up with my local friend, Sulaiman, and together we went on an adventure of a lifetime, from the urban city life to deep inside the desert on the Saudi border. 

This is my favorite video of the year so far, and I hope you enjoy!!

01NJ_QwwwWQ.title: Taking My Jewish Parents to a Muslim Country
01NJ_QwwwWQ.description:
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Get My Best Flight Hacks FREE! https://bit.ly/32sVpQV

I TOOK MY PARENTS TO TURKEY AND IT WAS AMAZING!  🇹🇷 

This was our 5th big international trip together, but it’s their first Muslim-majority country. Being Jewish, I knew that it would be an eye-opener for them, and it certainly was. 

We were led by our local Turkish friend, Anil — starting in Istanbul, then heading down South to Antakya, Gaziantep, Kahramanmaraş, and Kilis (on the Syrian border). 

From the mouth-watering cuisine to the ancient historical sites and everything in between - Turkey is just FANTASTIC (seriously, one of my favorite countries in the world) and it was special to experience it alongside my Mom and Dad. I think that this was my favorite trip yet with my parents. 

And most importantly, they now have a different perspective on Muslims and Islamic culture!!! They can fully understand that Jews and Muslims are SO similar, and that’s a beautiful thing :)

QNBQkupUENQ.title: My YouTube Was Hacked… Here’s How (full story)
QNBQkupUENQ.description:
- Join my Free Email Newsletter! https://www.drewbinsky.com/newsletter
- SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

The scariest situation of my entire life happened to me a few days ago. My main YouTube channel (this account) was hacked by a crypto scammer in China.  He changed the name of my account to “Ark Invest”, changed the profile picture, deleted all of my videos, and was live-streaming a Bitcoin video featuring Elon Musk's face on the thumbnail.  When I found out the news on a golf course in Wisconsin, I blacked out for 2 hours and couldn’t speak... Seriously. Thankfully, YouTube has been SO responsive and amazing to help me recover my account, and now it's back in full health.  

THIS IS A PSA REMINDER TO CHANGE ALL YOUR PASSWORDS AND DON’T CLICK ON RANDOM LINKS FROM RANDOM EMAILS.  HACKERS ARE EVERYWHERE, AND THEY ARE SMARTER THAN YOU.

Lastly, I want to say THANK YOU to this incredible community for all of your messages and support. I love you all!!!  I’m back!

TuzTRce1S-4.title: I Visited the 'Pakistan' of IRAN (Balochistan)
TuzTRce1S-4.description:
👫 Join 30,000+ Travelers in the JUST GO APP! Make friends, ask questions & get advice: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

I can't believe that I finally visited BALUCHISTAN! It's a region that spans Iran, Afghanistan, and Pakistan - but the majority of the area is completely forbidden for tourists to enter. I had the rare opportunity to visit Iranian Balochistan with my local friend Amin, along with his friends Hamzeh and Shaquib. The 4 of us spent 72 hours meeting locals, eating delicious food, and seeing the natural wonders of Baluchistan. And all I can say is that it was FANTASTIC. It's definitely my kind of place and a trip that I will remember for a lifetime.  

As I get older and visit more places, I can tell you that life is far more interesting the further off the beaten path you go.  Baluchistan is as good as it gets.  Thank you for watching! 

If you want to come to Iran, then DM Amin and he can organize your trip! https://instagram.com/amin.riasati

gW00UM85KaA.description:
Visit my Sponsor https://betterhelp.com/drewbinksy for 10% off your first month of therapy with BetterHelp

I'M BACK IN IRAN - My favorite country in the world!! This video takes you on a journey through my first 24 hours in the country. I met up with my local friend, Amin (who’s also a fantastic tour guide), and we explored the North-Western city of Tabriz. IRAN IS AS GOOD AS IT GETS, and I can't wait to share with you the next 5 episodes in this series!

CrQwlaCfpN8.title: I Tracked Down the President of Belize 🇧🇿
CrQwlaCfpN8.description:
Win a Free RT flight to meet me around the world by downloading Momento: https://bit.ly/3NGHwRO. And join their Discord! https://discord.gg/fkPmHEqvrf

WOW GUYS! I can’t believe that I successfully met my 2nd President/Head of State - Mr. Johnny Briceño of Belize - a beautiful country in Central America. 

Let's just say that it was not an easy journey to get here.  My flight was delayed by 4 hours, so I had to cancel my initial meeting with Mr. President.  And then it almost didn’t happen the next day because his schedule was so hectic...

So in between the anxiety of planning the meeting - I rented a car and explored all over this stunning tropical nation.  Belize really caught me by surprise!! 

PS - Is anyone still reading this? I’m not sure if people read captions anymore or not.  But I just want to personally thank you for being here with me. RJejNwupnhQ.title: Living Alone in an RV for 48 Hours!
RJejNwupnhQ.description:
Thanks to Sun Outdoors for sponsoring this video! Make sure to subscribe to their channel to enter their giveaway: https://youtube.com/c/SunOutdoorsOfficial

Ever since I was a kid, I’ve been fascinated by the RV life in America. I think it’s the greatest sub culture that we have in the USA, and I’ve never fully understood it until I made this video! 

I spent 2 full days living out of an RV in Arches National Park, Utah. Yes - sleeping, cooking, and frolicking around an RV park/campsite! I met some really interesting RVers who were stationed next to me, and I honestly had the time of my life. I hope you enjoy this story!

Intercity Public transportation systems (i.e. metros & subways) are something that I've always been obsessed with when I travel! I find it fascinating to learn about how people get from point A to point B (maybe because growing up in Phoenix, public transport is nonexistent!).

D93rYtaT3wI.title: Fasting in America's ONLY Muslim Town (Ramadan)
D93rYtaT3wI.description:
🌏 Get Exclusive NordVPN deal ➼ https://nordvpn.com/drewbinsky w/ coupon code 'drewbinsky'
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

Ever since I heard that Hamtramck, Michigan is America's ONLY Muslim-majority town, I knew that I had to visit (because I love Islam!!)  And it turned out to be one of the most incredible experiences that I've had within my own country, the United States of America.  

My friend @Jessica Kobeissi took me around her stomping grounds to introduce me to the culture that she grew up in, and I was completely amazed. So many Lebanese, Iraqis, Yemenis, Bangladeshis, Somalis, Syrians (etc) all living together in this suburban Michigan town called Hamtramck, along with nearby Dearborn.  

I went during the very first day of Ramadan - the holiest month in Islam - and I even participated in the fast myself. Watch until the end to see is breaking the fast (or iftar) at Jessica's friend's house.

The moral of this story is that America is SO BIG and SO DIVERSE, and there are many micro-communities to be discovered. Would you like to see more stories about the different communities in the USA? Please comment below and let me know - your feedback is so valuable to me. Thank you, and Ramadan Kareem to all who celebrate ❤️

JY-PNYkYccs.title: I Took an EXTREME RUSSIAN BATH and I Lost My Mind
JY-PNYkYccs.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ like-minded travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

This is the final video in my Russia (Siberia) series, and I think it’s the most entertaining! In the city of Novosibirsk, I walked into a traditional Russian bathhouse (called a banya), and I was greeted by a giant man named Herman. Herman ordered me to take off all my clothes and enter a 160-degree sauna (70C). I was then beaten by thorny Russian birch trees as well as a thick wooden stick. Then, I went outside to get an ice-cold bucket of water was poured on my head. 

The Russian banya experience took me back to the time when I did a Turkish bath, but this one was more intense! I absolutely love doing these activities - it’s the reason why I love traveling - to experience new cultures and learn about how other people spend their days. And truth be told, I felt very clean and relaxed after this bath — despite the pain that I went through!

ANNOUNCEMENT! I am really excited to share that my JUST GO APP is officially out for FREE on iPhone and android - and we already have 15,000 members!  JUST GO is an intimate place where you can connect, make new travel friends, join real-life meetups, and get inspired to travel! I launched my JUST GO community with Mighty Networks, an incredible all-in-one platform for community building (really, they are the BEST!) You can learn more about Mighty Networks on this link: https://www.mightynetworks.com/?via=drew

Lastly, I want to thank you for tuning into the last 5 weeks of stories in Russia/Siberia.  All content was filmed a month before Russia invaded Ukraine, so it comes with a very heavy heart.  I decided to share these videos because I strongly believe that the Russian people are NOT a representation on their crazy, evil dictator.  Please keep our friends and loved ones in Ukraine in your thoughts. It is absolutely horrible what they are going through, and I hope that this war ends soon. Thanks for watching.

pfrOrcxfYy0.title: Taking the TRANS-SIBERIAN TRAIN With Strangers
pfrOrcxfYy0.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ like-minded travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

This video was shot 4 weeks before Russia invaded Ukraine. I am devastated by what is happening and my thoughts and prayers go out to the victims of this war.  If you want to help, my friends @Yes Theoryare currently in Poland and have started a GoFundMe to help Ukrainian refugees with food, water, and necessities. They have already raised $500,000, and 100% of proceeds are going directly to help save lives: Donate here: https://bit.ly/3N5jQGJ

Okay, now onto the description of the video... Riding on the Trans-Siberian Train has been a bucket list adventure for me for as long as I can remember (8 years?). The train starts in Moscow and then travels 10,000 kilometers Eastbound across Siberia until it ends in Vladivostok.  I was lucky enough to catch Trans-Siberian train for a 30-hour leg – from Irkutsk to Novosibirsk – and it was one of the wildest travel experiences of my life.  Even in the middle of winter, where temperatures were around -30C, I couldn’t believe how scenic the views were out the window. It felt like a dream! 

On the Trans-Siberian train, I met two incredible characters – Gregory (the train conductor) and Sacha (the drunk passenger) who I shared the entire experience with.  I will never forget this train ride.  It was the journey of a lifetime, and I can’t wait to (hopefully) finish the rest of the adventure someday soon.  Siberia is truly a remarkable place.  Thank you for watching.

zOTrpwKhphU.title: How I Got DETAINED Sneaking into North Korea 🇰🇵
zOTrpwKhphU.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

7AqAs0YizkY.title: 4 Days in the WORLD'S COLDEST CITY (-40C) | Yakutsk, Russia
7AqAs0YizkY.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
✈️ Check out Miles Addict for travel hacks! www.milesaddict.com

This video was shot 3 weeks before Russia invaded Ukraine. I do NOT support this unprovoked war, and my thoughts go out to our friends in Ukraine. We love you. 

Welcome to YAKUTSK, RUSSIA (SIBERIA) - AKA the WORLD'S COLDEST CITY.  More than 300,000 people live here, where winter temperatures (like right now) reach as low as -55 Celsius. 

I went to Yakutsk a few weeks ago with my good friend Ammar from @Yes Theory.  The city is so remote that we had to take a 9-hour domestic flight from Moscow to get there. 

As soon as we arrived in this cold winter wonderland, I couldn’t believe my eyes.  Completely frozen trees, frozen pipelines, frozen cars… frozen everything!!  But underneath the layers of jackets are extremely friendly faces and warm smiles.  And that’s what I came here to learn about - humanity.  Who are the Yakutian people? How do they survive these brutally cold winters? 

This video takes you on a 4-day journey through the world’s coldest city - Yakutsk.  I think you will be quite surprised to discover that Yakutsk is actually a normal city, just like anywhere else. It just happens to be extremely cold! 

Thank you to my local friends Maria #1 and Maria #2 (from @Life in Yakutia) for showing me around! And thanks to Andrey for the awesome work behind the camera. And thank YOU so much for watching — this video is really special to me and many long hours of work have gone into it.  

Have a great Sunday and I’ll see you next week.

9Jw3Z0s3DrI.title: I Just Left Russia. My Thoughts on Invading Ukraine
9Jw3Z0s3DrI.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

I love Ukraine. I’ve always said that it’s one of the most underrated countries in Europe. The historical sites and monuments are breathtaking. The people are very humble and friendly and I have nothing but incredible memories during my 10 day trip to Ukraine in 2015.

I just spent 3 weeks traveling across Eastern Russia (Siberia) and while I really enjoyed my trip, in terms of culture and adventure — the politics just don’t make sense to me. I just woke up to the news that Russia invaded Ukraine, and I don't understand why anyone wants to start another war.  This is devastating. 

My heart aches for the 44 million people living in Ukraine, many who are currently listening to the sounds of explosions and don’t know what tomorrow will bring. I wish nothing but health and safety for all of my Ukrainians friends out there. We are keeping you in our thoughts and prayers 💔🇺🇦

My first Russia video goes live on Sunday (two days from now) and then for the next 4 consecutive weeks, you will see episodes from my Russia (Siberia) series.  I want you all to know that the filming of these stories took place BEFORE the war has started, so I will proceed with sharing them as planned.  Thank you for your understanding, and I will see you guys on Sunday.

Before my trip to Saudi Arabia, I had no idea that I was allowed to visit Medina. It’s the 2nd holiest city in Islam and I always assumed that it was off-limits to non-Muslims (similar to Mecca) — but I was wrong!  Anybody is allowed to visit Medina (even Jews!), they just can’t venture inside the gates of the Prophet’s Mosque.

6PtgdyLuZic.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75

📝 Get My Best Flight Hacks FREE! https://bit.ly/32sVpQV

Hello from my 197th & FINAL country... SAUDI ARABIA! 🇸🇦 I'm almost in tears as I type this... I can't believe that I finally made it here.  I'm having a blast so far and I can't wait to share my adventure with you in this $10 video! 

However, it is bittersweet to announce that this will be my final $10 episode ever. I have decided to retire my most popular series after 60+ episodes and 1+ billion video views because all good things come to an end, and it's time to move on to telling bigger and better stories in my future travels.

FYwwX2gZSR8.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

📝 Get My Best Flight Hacks FREE! https://bit.ly/32sVpQV

Prepare yourselves to hear the story of Yeonmi Park because it’s heavy.  

When she was a teenager, Yeonmi escaped from North Korea to China.  What she experienced was horrible — being sold as a sex slave by border officials, walking across Mongolia in the middle of winter and nearly dying of starvation.  

But Yeonmi made it out alive, and now she lives happily in Chicago.  She is outspoken about the terrible regime in North Korea and she voices her thoughts on her YouTube Channel, and through various best selling books.  I invite you to share your opinions about Yeonmi’s story and about North Korea in general in the comments below. 

Hope you had a very Merry Christmas and remember that freedom is not always free. 

I’ll see you in the next year when I’m kicking off my Saudi Arabia videos!!!

RASTA VIBES!  I've been very interested in the Rastafarian culture since I got hooked on Bob Marley as a teenager. I mean, wasn't everyone obsessed with Bob Marley at some point in their lives?  He is a living legend! 

It turns out that Bob Marley was one of the first people to bring his Rasta culture to all corners of the world.  And believe it or not, Rastafari is not just a culture or a social movement -- it's the world's newest religion that started in the 1930s (as an offshoot of Christianity).  Rasta people typically have dreadlocks, listen to reggae music, eat vegan food and smoke a lot of ganja. 

I went to Jamaica to learn more about the Rastafarian people, culture, and lifestyle -- and I ended up spending 48 hours with an amazing community in the Blue Mountains.  Here is the full story! Share this video with your friends if you enjoyed :)

First off, I want to say THANK YOU for all your kind words and messages these past few days. It feels surreal to be able to say the sentence, “I have been to every single country in the world!” There will be many incredible stories being made these next 2 weeks as I travel across Saudi Arabia. 

But let’s not forget about Palau! This is my last video from this beautiful Pacific-island nation, and it’s one of my favorites!  Palau has a population of less than 18,000 residents. For comparison, my University (Wisconsin-Madison) was two times larger than that! 

I challenged myself to see if I could throw the biggest meet-up/party that this country has ever seen. In order to do that, I had to get permission from the Palau’s Visitors Authority as well as the President himself.  

Let’s just say that it was one of the most fun events I’ve ever thrown!!!  I hope you enjoy this story, and thanks for watching my Palau series.  It’s one of the most beautiful countries in the world and I can’t wait to go back!

oMMQnM-abUM.title: I FINALLY MADE IT TO EVERY COUNTRY IN THE WORLD 🌍
oMMQnM-abUM.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

October 29, 2021 at 1:31AM - I crossed the border into Saudi Arabia, my 197th & FINAL country! 🇸🇦🙏 

I'm feeling lots of emotions right now, and it will take some time to digest over the next few weeks as I travel across Saudi Arabia, but I just want to say first and foremost, THANK YOU ❤️

Thank you to my better half, Deanna, for believing in me since we met 6 years ago.  Thank you to my loving parents and family for supporting me.  Thank you to all of my best friends for pushing me during the hard times.  Thank you to all the strangers and local tour guides I met, in far away places, for keeping me safe and secure.  And most importantly, if you’re reading this, THANK YOU. 

I’m so grateful for this amazing YouTube community.  I want you guys to know that for the past 4 years, I've poured my blood, sweat and tears into telling the best stories about people and culture.  And I am so freaking happy that you guys have been able to travel with me as I visited all 197 countries in the world.  Thank you for all your comments, questions, advice and words of encouragement. Without you, I do not stand here right now, in tears, at the Jeddah airport. 

It has taken me 10 long years (almost exactly to the day) to achieve this goal, since I moved to Prague to study abroad in Jan, 2012.  I was 20 years old back then. Now I am 30.  It’s crazy to think that I’ve been on the road nonstop, roughly 3,600 days, without taking a break. 

But I made it!!! And I’m feeling as happy as ever.  I did it.  I FREAKING DID IT!!! I can now say that I have visited every single country in the world. 

This is not the end of Drew Binsky.  It’s only the beginning!  I will now be chasing the STORY, not so much the COUNTRY.  This means a bigger team that can help take my videos to the next level!  But there's a lot of exciting projects that I'm working on -- below are links to favorite ones:

1) My 2nd YT channel is called “Faces of the World,” where I will be telling you the most inspiring ‘people stories’ around the globe.  Subscribe here: https://bit.ly/3vQNSFY

2) My JUST GO Holiday Drop theme is “We Are All The Same!” Coming  outon Nov 21. Here’s a link to the store: https://shopjustgo.com/

3) I’ve launched JUST GO MEET UPS, which is like the coolest travel club everyone in this community to meet up in your city! Joni our Instagram for updates: https://www.instagram.com/justgomeetups/

4) My Travel Hacking Course is live, Get the 1st Chapter FREE! https://www.drewbinsky.com/course

5) I am launching the first travel-focused NFT collection called Travel Tokens. More info here: https://traveltokensnft.com/

6) I am launching both a book and a docuseries in the next 1-2 years!   More info on the film can be found here: http://drewbinskydocumentary.com/

THANK YOU, ONCE AGAIN, FROM THE BOTTOM OF MY HEART.  I LOVE YOU!! THIS IS NOT THE END OF DREW BINSKY, IT'S ONLY THE BEGINNING!

✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

This story is amazing! I've been to over 700 airports around the world, and Angaur Terminal in the Pacific island nation of Palau is by far the SMALLEST!!!  

My local friend Sachi and I took a propeller plane down to Pelileu, but we decided to take a pit stop in Angaur only to see this terminal.  It has so much charm and character!  There are no walls, no bathrooms, and no electricity. There's no TSA pre-check or security lines.   Just a tiny bench to sit on while you wait for your plane to arrive.  For aviation geeks like me, this was really special to experience and just another reason to love Palau!

REAL LIFE UPDATE:  I am touching down in Saudi Arabia in 4 days -- MY 197th AND FINAL COUNTRY!!  Stay tuned for a huge video drop when I arrive which explains my biggest realization from visiting every country in the world, and what's next for Drew Binsky. In case you're wondering, I already spent 11 days in Jamaica (that content will be shared soon), but I just want to give you a current life update because this is the most exciting week of my life! 10 years of nonstop travel and FINALLY, I am about to be one of ~300 people in history to visit every country in the world! OMGGG I am having the time of my life in this tiny Pacific-island nation called Palau (my 195th country visited!) Have you ever heard of Palau before?  It's one of the most beautiful countries in the world in terms of beaches and nature -- but it's also one of the most expensive because almost everything here needs to be imported.  With that being said, find out how many things I could purchase around the island for $10.  

Watch this video until the end, it takes an emotional turn when I get to Pelileu. The island where my Grandpa Jack fought in WWII and got shot in the leg.  Before he passed away a few months ago, I was able to hear his harrowing Palau battle stories and I traced his footsteps. Thanks for watching, it means a lot to me.  RIP Grandpa ❤️

Follow @Drew Binsky  for more stories from EVERY country, and join me on https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

I CAN'T BELIEVE I MADE IT TO PALAU - COUNTRY #195!!! 🇵🇼  Only 2 countries left (Jamaica & Saudi Arabia) until I can officially say that I've visited every country in the world!  

It feels wonderful to be back on the road again, after a few months of hanging back in the U.S.   This trip to Palau is one that I've been looking forward to for a LONG TIME, and finally -- after an 18 month delay due to closed borders -- I was on one of the first commercial flights back to this lovely Pacific Island nation. 

And guess what? I had the chance to meet the President of Palau at his office!  He gave me 2 hours of his time and I was able to ask him so many of my burning questions.  

What an adventure my first few days in Palau have been, and I can't wait to show you more of this pristine country over the next 4 weeks.  Trust me when I tell you that these stories are going to blow your mind! 

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from EVERY country, and join me on https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Is Puerto Rico the U.S.A? They have U.S. passports, use U.S. dollars, and send mail with the US postal service… but they speak Spanish, aren’t allowed to vote for President, and are VERY proud of their Latino culture.

I just revisited the island after 18 years, and all I can say is WOW! This place is buzzing with life and happiness. Join me as I try to make sense of life in Puerto Rico, while seeing how many things I can get for $10 USD.

ElgeqJp6ddo.title: 4 Reasons I Love Islam and Muslim People
ElgeqJp6ddo.description:
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Get My Best Flight Hacks FREE! https://bit.ly/32sVpQV

At this point in my life, I’ve spent more than 1 year traveling across Muslim-majority countries.  And many of them (like Iran, Afghanistan, Tajikistan, Syria, Indonesia) are my favorite nations in the world! 

Growing up as a Jew in the USA, I was told by many that Muslims are bad people… but that can’t be farther away from the truth!   There is a huge misconception about Muslims.  They are some of the most respectful, hospitable, and friendly souls on the planet, and I learned this from experience.  

As I reflect here in Nouakchott, Mauritania on the last day of 8 months on the road, I wanted to share some of my honest thoughts about Islam.  

I hope some of you guys can relate, and if you can, please let me know in the comments below 🙏

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on IG: http://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Growing up as a Jew in the USA, I was told by many that Muslims are bad people… but that can’t be farther away from the truth!   There is a huge misconception about Muslims.  They are some of the most respectful, hospitable, and friendly souls on the planet, and I learned this from experience.  

As I reflect here in Nouakchott, Mauritania on the last day of 8 months on the road, I wanted to share some of my honest thoughts about Islam.

I9BVICBCdXY.title: How My Friend Escaped Afghanistan (to Australia)
I9BVICBCdXY.description:
My heart aches with Afghanistan.  It's one of my favorite countries in the world and I'm devastated by what's been happening. Many of you have been asking about Noor -- my beloved Afghan friend and tour guide.   I spent every moment of 4 weeks traveling around Afghanistan with him by my side --  he's one of the most sincere and down-to-earth people I've ever met, who has a passion for sharing the beauty of his country.   

I've stayed silent to protect Noor's safety, but now I'm so happy to break the news that he and his family have arrived safely in Melbourne, Australia!  They managed to get on one of the final evacuation military airplanes out of Kabul. I was able to catch up with Noor via zoom yesterday, and he shared the harrowing details of escaping Kabul at the last second.   Here is our full conversation. 

ORGANIZATIONS TO DONATE TO:

If you'd like to donate to help those in Afghanistan, please see the following 2 links.  If you aren't able to donate, don't worry because just by watching this video you are helping -- all proceeds will be sent to both fundraisers. 

1. https://fundly.com/support-afghan-guides-and-fixers-1

This was started by my friend Matt with an attempt to get all Afghan tour guides, fixers and drivers to safety (Noor's colleagues).   All funds will support transportation, resettlement, and general humanitarian needs for those displaced or trying to leave the country. 

2. https://www.stimulus.app/campaigns/afghan-women-in-danger/

This was started by my friend and fellow traveler Omid.  It's urgent aid for Afghan women refugees. They have partnered with "Women For Afghan Women" to identify refugees who have recently landed in the US.  All donations go directly to these women and families. They provide cash grants starting at $300 per person to help with their transition.

Thank you for watching, and I'll see you on Sunday with the next episode from Mauritania. 

#Afghanistan #Refugee #Kabul

I don't often talk about the negatives of travel, because there is so much positivity to share!  But truth be told, life of a full time traveler is not always rainbows and ponies.  Not at all.

In this video, I open up to you a bit and share why AIRPORTS are the most stressful part of the travel experience for me.   Airports are the main driver for my severe anxiety -- because of all the immigration questions, checkpoints, police encounters -- while trying to hide my identity as a YouTuber.   Because believe it or not, being a YouTuber (i.e. Journalist) is frowned upon in MANY countries around the world. 

Does anyone else out there feel the same about airports? I'd love to hear from you in the comments below.

jkujoUejH0I.title: BAGHDAD STREET FOOD TOUR (5 Dishes for $15)
jkujoUejH0I.description:
🌍 GET 50% OFF MY TRAVEL HACKING COURSE by using discount code YOUTUBE:  https://www.drewbinsky.com/course
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

This is my final video from Iraq.  I've had the time of my life traveling through this country and I hope you've enjoyed my stories here over the last 9 weeks. 

On my final day in Iraq, I met up with my long time Iraqi friend, Baderkhan, who you might know well from the many videos we shot together in Iraqi Kurdistan.  We hit the streets of Baghdad (his hometown), and tried all of the best street food that the city has to offer!  We were able to eat 5 dishes for just $15USD total, now that's a bargain!

Little did we know how scary this video would be to shoot -- I left my passport in my hotel room (which is a BIG no-no in Iraq), so we tried to dodge the police the entire day.  If you can remember last week, I was thrown into a police station in the marshlands for using my GoPro... Find out if we made it to the end without any police encounters!

Also - it's with a heavy heart to explain that 24 hours after we shot this video, there was massive attack in the exact same market, on the exact same street, during the exact same time of the day.  I was devastated to hear the news, and I couldn't believe our luck - we escaped it by just 24 hours.   My deepest condolences go out to all of the loved ones that were lost in this horrible act, and I hope the city will return back to its glory days.

Thanks again for watching my videos and I look forward to sharing my next stories in Dubai and Mauritania!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from EVERY country, and join me on Insta! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky  

#DrewBinsky #Baghdad #StreetFood

vP7V4K73MLY.title: I Slept in a Strangers Home in Iraq. It Was Wild
vP7V4K73MLY.description:
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 MY TRAVEL HACKING COURSE goes live on Aug 12!  Sign up for my newsletter to get 50% off within the first 24 hours: https://bit.ly/3CDsZRA

Dear Friends: This is my favorite story from Iraq.  I hope you will watch to the end so you can learn about the unique lifestyles of the 'Marsh Arabs.'

Iraq is famous for their "Iraqi Marshlands" (also known as Mesopotamian Marshes).  It's a rare, aquatic landscapes in the desert, stretching hundreds of miles across Southeastern Iraq into Southwestern Iran. 

In fact, these marshes were one of the largest wetland ecosystems in the world until sadly, they were drained in the 1980s and 1990s under a former presidents' rule.  However, in recent years, the marshlands are back to higher water levels and it was awarded as a UNESCO world heritage site in 2016.

I visited the Iraqi Marshlands with my buddy Alvaro for 24 hours, and I documented the entire adventure for you to see.  I hope you enjoy this story.  I will never forget how amazing this experience was! 

Follow me on Instagram Stories to follow my travels in real time! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

This story is a little bit of a different from my style, but it's one that I feel is incredibility necessary to share.  

While at a coffee shop in Baghdad, I met a young lady named Aya.  We sat down and starting chatting, and she started telling me the most somber and vivid stories about how she managed to survive BOTH the recent wars in Syria and Iraq.  I asked for her permission to interview her and share her story, and she was happy to do so because the world needs more empathy for the people of Iraq and Syria. 

Aya is one of the strongest, most resilient women I've ever met, and I hope you take away something powerful from this video.   And realize how good you have it. 

Thanks for watching, and I'll see you guys next week with a more positive story from Iraq.  For now, you can catch me on IG Stories for live updates from my trip! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

9NDswjk6GUA.title: The World's BIGGEST Pilgrimage (Karbala, Iraq)
9NDswjk6GUA.description:
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get 50% off my Travel Hacking Course:  https://bit.ly/3xNlPHD
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

WELCOME TO KARBALA, IRAQ.  This is the site of the world's largest pilgrimage, where every October, over 15 MILLION Shia Muslims walk from neighboring countries to show respect to Imam Hussain's shrine (grandson of prophet Muhammad).   Even though I am not visiting in October, I can feel the spirit in the air unlike any place I've ever been. 

The mosques and mausoleums are STUNNING, and somehow, I got special VIP access into the back room to meet with the boss... and he gave me permission to film inside.  This kind of permission is unheard of!

But my favorite thing about Karbala is the hospitality. You've probably noticed a theme by now - that the Middle East has the most hospitable people in the world and a perfect example of this is Karbala! 

The main mosque provides hundreds of thousands (if not millions) of FREE meals to anyone who stops by.   I've never seen anything like it in my life... And not only that, but the local people will open their doors to all visitors.  

We randomly got invited into a family's home where they cooked us a 10 course meal. 

All of that and more in this amazing episode, which I hope will change your perspective about Iraq.  

If you're still reading this, just know that I love you and thanks so much for watching my videos and supporting me over the years.  I am in my happiest place right now, traveling through Iraq proper, and I'm just so grateful to be able to share these stories with you.   More to come next week! 

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country and join me on https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/.

FTBHGfULSC8.title: Exploring the World's First City
FTBHGfULSC8.description:
📝 Thanks to Morning Brew for sponsoring this video! Sign up to become smarter in 5 minutes for free: https://bit.ly/mbdrewbinsky
🌎 JUST GO DROP: https://shop.drewbinsky.com/
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

The first time I heard about Babylon was in first grade -- my teacher taught me that human civilization started in ancient Mesopotamia, at the intersection point of the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers.   Well, not only did I just visit that exact place where the two rivers meet (in the center of Iraq), but I ventured deep into BABYLON.  This ancient civilization dates back to the 19th Century BC, and is absolutely mind blowing.   The best part is that my buddy Alvaro and I were THE ONLY ONES THERE. 

If these ruins were in a country like Italy or Spain, then they would be the most visited sites on earth... But sadly, we are deep in the heart of Iraq, a nation that has been torn apart by war and turmoil over the last 30 years. 

I've been to 194 countries and I've seen a lot of cool things and places, but this ranks up there as one of the best.  It might just be number 1.  It's really hard to put into words the feeling of walking these grounds, which are still being excavated to this day. 

I hope that you guys enjoy our adventure around Babylon and that you learn something new.  I am so grateful to have this platform and be able to share my experiences with you, because so few outsiders get to come here.   Thanks for reading this and I'll see you next week!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country, and follow my trip to Iraq and beyond on IG Stories: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

O2O3eCzqvY0.title: I Found Saddam Hussein’s Abandoned Palace (Iraq)
O2O3eCzqvY0.description:
📱 Text me: 310 349 3854 (i'll text back!)
📝 Join my Newsletter: https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

After wandering around Baghdad for a few days, the real Iraqi adventure has just began...  My buddy Alvaro and I road tripped to the outskirts of Babylon - the world's first city dating back to 19th Century BC -- and we stumbled upon a MASSIVE palace that overlooks the ancient ruins. 

We parked our car, and wandered inside.  It was Saddam Hussein's former palace, which is now totally abandoned.  It was so scary to knock down doors and crawl through shattered glass and broken bottles, but it was an experience I'll never forget.   You have to see it to believe it!

Stay tuned for next Sunday's video, where I take you on a journey across ancient Babylon!  Iraq is as good as it gets 🇮🇶

Follow  @Drew Binsky  for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on IG Stories to see my trip behind the scenes: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

n5aWhaLl7sk.title: Inside the Secret Bubble of Venezuela's ULTRA RICH
n5aWhaLl7sk.description:
► Thank you to my friends at Corona for sponsoring this video.
📝To win a postcard + banknote from Venezuela, join my email newsletter! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

This is my final video in this memorable 9-part series in Venezuela.  I am so sad to leave this country – it’s my favorite in all of Latin America and I know that I’ll be back someday soon!

You may have noticed that many of the videos in my Venezuela series have revolved around the unfortunate economical situation (etc) --  but in this video, I wanted to share with you the other side of the story...  The high class!  

I was shocked to find out that Caracas has an ULTRA WEALTHY inner bubble, with expensive restaurants, swanky bars, high end shopping and exclusive golf clubs.   My friend Emmanuel (@DosLocosDeViaje) and I spent my last day in town exploring the luxury life, and it was a blast!

If you’re still reading this, thank you from the bottom of my heart for tuning into this series.  Thank you for all of your comments, questions and thoughts.  It’s a great opportunity to tell stories in a country as misconceived as Venezuela, and it's a true pleasure to open your eyes to real life, real people and real situations happening on these streets.   As for now, I’m making a stop home (Arizona) before heading on a road trip around IRAQ Proper – stay tuned for more amazing stories!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more videos from every country, and join me on Instagram Stories! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

GkyLAKzznwg.description:
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
🇻🇪 VENEZUELA IS CRAZY. AND AWESOME. FOR REAL!

I'm stoked to have joined the Sony Alpha team (!) and I've partnered with them to GIVEAWAY 3 of their newest ZV-1 vlogging cameras.  To win: follow @drewbinsky and @sonyalpha on Instagram and comment 2 sentences below on what you'd do with the camera.  I'm also including a signed postcard from Venezuela and a 10,000 VZ banknote in each box. Yay!
------------
I recently hit the streets of Caracas with my local friends Gabo and Emmanuel to see if we could exchange $100 USD for local Venezuelan Bolivares.   At the time when I shot this video, $100 USD was about 170 Million Bolivares, but now at the time of posting, $100 USD is about 300 million Bolivares.  The currency has depreciated by almost 100%.  

We spent ALL day walking into small shops, bakeries, market vendors (etc) in Caracas and unfortunately, we were only able to exchange $62...  Yes, we really did have a backpack full of cash on our backs.  It was wild. 

The economic crisis in Venezuela is very sad and it's hard to comprehend what's happening.  And how fast it's happening.  I have empathy for the people here who are suffering to make ends meet, but instead of dwelling on the situation, it's been refreshing to see many of the locals being resilient and optimistic for a brighter future.    I made this video to give you a glimpse of real life on the streets of Caracas, because I think it's important to give you an honest perspective. I love this city and country with all of my heart - it has the BEST food, hospitality and culture in all of South America 💛💙❤️  If you're still reading this, I want you to know that I love you and thanks for supporting my channel.  I pour my blood, sweat tears into making these videos and I hope they are opening up your eyes to the world.  Happy Sunday and Mother's Day -- I love you, mom!

PFJn9vz9qao.description:

I JUST VISITED THE WORLD'S MOST DANGEROUS SLUM IN VENEZUELA and it was one of the craziest experiences of my life.  It's called Petare, and it's basically a sub-district of Caracas with a population of over 1 million people who live on the top of a mountain.  

None of my local Venezuelan friends ever has the courage to venture deep inside Petare before, but together we decided to give it a try and it was eye opening to say the least.  We ended up making a local friend, Marquito, who showed us around, invited us into his home and introduced us to his family & friends.  

There was one moment on the street where things got pretty tense, but other than that, it was safer than I expected and it a humbling experience to meet with the people and feel their energy.  Even though they may not have much, they are very friendly and welcoming people and I would go back in a heartbeat.

-7Doy0sfXqQ.title: The Truth About Venezuela's Gas Crisis
-7Doy0sfXqQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► 📝 Join my Newsletter & you'll be sent a secret video of my 3 best travel hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

As many of you may know, Venezuela has been experiencing the worst economic downfall in the history of the world.  It's more than twice as severe as the U.S. Great Depression, and I simply cannot ignore this sad reality as I am visiting the country...  

The main driver for this economic crisis is oil. 

Nearly a century ago, massive oil reserves were discovered off the Northern coast of Venezuela, which is why the country used to be the wealthiest in Latin America (in the 1960s and 1970s)... But sadly, a series of poor decisions, mismanagement and (recent) U.S. sanctions has crippled its economy to pieces.  Nowadays, despite having one of the world's largest oil reserves, there is a HUGE gas shortage and the locals have to wait in their car HOURS or even DAYS just to fill up their gas tank.  It's a very sad reality and I've never seen anything like it before in all of my travels to 194 countries.  My heart is with the people of Venezuela and I sincerely hope that the situation gets better so the country can thrive again like the olden days. 

Join me in this part-documentary, part-adventure vlog as I educate you about the devastating gas crisis in Venezuela.

t6Lco7BZZt0.title: I Found a Venezuelan Paradise Hidden from the World
t6Lco7BZZt0.description:
► JUST GO Shirts & Hats available: https://shop.drewbinsky.com/ 
► SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

I just spent 24 hours in the remote Venezuelan island called Chuao, tucked away somewhere on the beautiful Caribbean Sea.   Chuao was SO unexpected and beautiful... I am still pinching myself if this was a dream or if it was reality.

In this video, I take you on the journey to discover Chuao -- from the pristine, untouched beaches to the friendly, hospitable locals and the world famous cacao (which is soooo delicious!) This island is a paradise unlike any other I've seen through 194 countries, and I will absolutely be returning back here in the future.

Honestly speaking, Venezuela is NOT as scary as you've heard about on the news - especially when you get outside of Caracas.  Yes, there is a devastating economic crisis and massive hyperinflation, but that doesn't mean that you will get robbed or shot at by walking around on the street.  It doesn't mean that there are no restaurants to eat at or things to do.   Life does exist, somewhat normally, in many parts of the country just like here in Chuao. 

If you're still reading this, I want to say thank you so much for tuning into my videos in Venezuela.  I'm having a lot of fun on this trip and making these stories, and the best are yet to come!

After making 1,100+ videos in 194 countries, THIS IS MY FAVORITE VIDEO THAT I'VE EVER MADE and the one that you've all been waiting for!  

What Can $10 Get in Venezuela?  

In this epic adventure, I take you on the bustling streets of Caracas and through the beautiful beach towns of Morrocoy to see how many things I could purchase with $10 USD, which at the time I made this video, was 14.7 MILLION Venezuelan Bolivares... Right now, $10 USD is equal to 22 million Bolivares, it's absolutely crazy. 

Despite Venezuela's economic crisis and massive hyperinflation, the cost of every day items is getting more expensive, which makes it even harder for the local people to afford basic things like bread and water.  It's really sad, and I hope the situation gets better because Venezuelans are some of the warmest and most hospitable people I've ever met.  More to come soon from Venezuela!

After making 1,100+ videos in 194 countries, THIS IS MY FAVORITE VIDEO THAT I'VE EVER MADE and the one that you've all been waiting for!  

What Can $10 Get in Venezuela?  

In this epic adventure, I take you on the bustling streets of Caracas and through the beautiful beach towns of Morrocoy to see how many things I could purchase with $10 USD, which at the time I made this video, was 14.7 MILLION Venezuelan Bolivares... Right now, $10 USD is equal to 22 million Bolivares, it's absolutely crazy. 

Despite Venezuela's economic crisis and massive hyperinflation, the cost of every day items is getting more expensive, which makes it even harder for the local people to afford basic things like bread and water.  It's really sad, and I hope the situation gets better because Venezuelans are some of the warmest and most hospitable people I've ever met.  More to come soon from Venezuela!

Y-YGYtG9hm4.title: I Survived a Fatal Bus Crash in India (full story)
Y-YGYtG9hm4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE to my UNSEEN Channel! https://bit.ly/2Oq6fjX
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my 3 Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

In today's video, I tell you my craziest travel story in full detail.  6 years ago, I was in a fatal bus crash in India during my 3-month solo backpacking adventure across the country.  It happened to me when I was en route from Udaipur to Jodhpur in the Rajasthan state.  I was the only foreigner on the bus, and the only English speaker.  The bus crashed around 1AM local time, in the middle of nowhere.  It was the only time that I had to put my hand over my pulse to see if my heart was still beating.  2 people did not make it out alive.   I get anxiety just thinking about what happened. 

I do not hate India - I have had some incredible experiences around the country.  The bus crash could have happened to me in any place, but unfortunately it happened in India.  I am happy that I made it out alive and thankful to continue traveling. 

What's the scariest thing that has ever happened to you on your trips? Please comment below (I read all of them)!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on Instagram: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

dndD_4a51XI.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► JUST GO MERCH launching on Mar 21, get early access here: https://bit.ly/3c6WhM4

Whenever I visit a new city or country, the very first place that I like to go is the market - and it's where the majority of my $10 videos are shot!  Street markets are where I can get a general understanding of the people and culture.  I can see what they are eating, what they are wearing and how they interact with each other.  Markets give me a really good first impression for how my trip will unfold, and honestly, they are so much fun to experience!

In today's video, I take you on a journey inside my 5 favorite street markets around the world - from Afghanistan to Libya, Tajikistan, Iran and Syria - I hope you enjoy!

Admittedly, I had no idea that the town of CUENCA existed before my trip to Ecuador, but I'm SO HAPPY that we made a spontaneous decision to come here on our final days in the country.

Cuenca represents everything that I enjoy about South America - charming cobblestone streets, tasty street food, historic churches and hidden wonders on every corner.  Sometimes when you just take a spontaneous trip, they turn out to be the best decisions -- and that's exactly how I feel about Cuenca.

The next time you find yourself in South America, or Ecuador in specific, I highly recommend giving Cuenca a visit!

FlzjT-VkgTc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

In today's video, I want to introduce you to my friend Esteban who comes from Ecuador.   As soon as he found out that I was coming to visit his country, he reached out on Instagram and offered to show me around, alongside his brother Gustavo. 

I didn't know much about Esteban before we met, but after spending 12 days getting to know him across Ecuador, I learned that he is one of the strongest and most optimistic souls that I've ever met. 

Several years ago, his friend threw him out of a moving car and he lost 1/3rd of his skull.  Doctors weren't sure if he would make it.  He had to completely relearn how to speak Spanish and English from scratch.  

But through perseverance and positive thinking, Esteban has gotten back on his feet and is now living a normal life.    Here is his full story. 

Thank you, Esteban and your brother Gustavo for showing me an incredible time around Ecuador.  I can't wait to be back again sometime soon!

6K_C-rYVPoY.title: COVID RELATIONSHIP (How We Manage Long Distance)
6K_C-rYVPoY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

For anyone who is in a long-distance relationship, especially if both partners come from different countries, then you know how difficult the past year has been during covid. 

Deanna and I have only see each other two times in the past 4 months, once in Turkey and now we are in Tanzania.  We are forced to keep meeting in 3rd party countries, because the Philippines is completely closed and they are not allowing any foreigners to enter for any reason.   Even though our apartment, our puppy and our lives are set in Manila, I am unable to go back home and it really crushes me. 

This is a video that Deanna and I wanted to make to share with you some of our struggles during this time, and we hope that some of you out there can relate to us.  If you are in a long-distance relationship and you've faced similar problems, we'd love to hear from you in the comments below!

Stay strong everyone, we will get through these dark days together ❤️

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on IG: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

In my latest $10 episode (45th episode overall) I take you on the bustling streets of Moshi, Tanzania - a small, yet energetic town on the foothills of Mt. Kilimanjaro.   I teamed up with my friend and local celebrity named Nick Reynolds (AKA Bongozozo), and together we had a blast hitting the markets and also hitting the links (this is the first time that I've been able to purchase a full 18 holes of golf for under $10!).

Truth be told, I wasn't expecting this video to be as fun as it was -- and I'm hungry for more!!!  I'm having the time of my life on this trip to Tanzania and I hope you guys are enjoying the content.

ul0oMWpieyc.title: 8 DAYS IN TANZANIA (Africa's Best Country!) 🇹🇿
ul0oMWpieyc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I'M SO HAPPY that I made it back to the incredible East African nation of TANZANIA!  My previous (and only) visit here was back in Jan 2018, where I only visited the island of Zanzibar.  But I really missed out because the people, culture, food and nature on the mainland is just about as good as you can find anywhere on this planet. 

My friends at Qatar Airways reached out and offered to fly me and Deanna on business class to Tanzania, and we couldn't say no!  I've never had a better flying experience in my life... and Tanzania was just amazing! We began our trip in Arusha, then went to Ngorongoro Conservation area before heading deep into the Serengeti for 3 nights and finally ending in a town called Moshi.  Tanzania is a phenomenal country inside and out, and I can't wait to show you more of this country over the coming 2 weeks!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on Instagram: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Pt1uw9hTxmA.title: VIRAL COFFIN DANCERS (internet meme legends)
Pt1uw9hTxmA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

Have you ever seen that viral internet meme of the guys dancing with coffins at a funeral? Well, the group is from Accra, Ghana, and I was able to track them down the other day and tell you their unbelievable story of how it all started. 

The main guy, Benjamin Aidoo, first got the idea to turn a funeral into a celebration about 20 years ago, and today it has grown into a massive business with over 100 people working for him.  

Benjamin and the guys have a really interesting perspective of death.  Instead of mourning the deceased, they decide to make it a huge celebration to bring happiness to their lives.   What do you guys think about this concept?

What an amazing experience to meet the viral coffin dancers and learn about their lives.  I have a feeling that this won't be the last time you will see them!

1ThcD6LXqIQ.title: I Bought a Cow for $200 in Ghana
1ThcD6LXqIQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

In all of my travels, I have never purchased a cow (or even thought of purchasing a cow) -- but when my buddy Wode Maya told me that it would be possible on our road trip to Northern Ghana, I was intrigued. 

After we spent 3 amazing days in a small village called Funsi,  I wanted to provide them with a gift -- and instead of money, I was advised that a cow would be more appreciated because it could feed almost every single person in the village. 

So we asked around to find a cow farmer, and went on an adventure through the fields to negotiate with a not--so-friendly cow farmer and deliver it back to the village. 

It was such a heart-warming moment and I'm so grateful for this experience.  More stories to come from the amazing country of GHANA!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world!  And join me on IG for live updates: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

So we asked around to find a cow farmer, and went on an adventure through the fields to negotiate with a not--so-friendly cow farmer and deliver it back to the village. 

It was such a heart-warming moment and I'm so grateful for this experience.  More stories to come from the amazing country of GHANA!

ivJpNS9XwJY.title: WOMEN OF AFGHANISTAN (6 inspiring stories)
ivJpNS9XwJY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

When traveling around Afghanistan (and other Muslim-majority countries), I receive many comments about why no women appear in my videos.   

The reason is because these societies are largely dominated by men -- and men are the ones who are commonly seen on the streets, driving cars, working in shops and eating in restaurants.   For the most part, women stay  at home to watch their kids, clean the house, prepare food, etc. This is how the culture has been functioning for thousands and thousands of years, especially right here in Afghanistan. 

BUT, that doesn't mean that there aren't as many women as men who are doing inspiring things!   In general, women are shy of the camera and they don't want to be exposed for cultural reasons, which is something that I always respect and honor.   This is why I do not show many women in my videos. 

However, over the last few weeks as I've traveled around Afghanistan, I've been able to sit down with 6 incredible women entrepreneurs to hear their stories.   They all have amazing things to say!! 

I really enjoyed making this video and I hope that you guys enjoy listening what they have to say, because as we all know, women make the world go 'round!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and join me on Instagram! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

ew8R7p9qhws.title: AFGHAN STREET FOOD (delicious and cheap!!)
ew8R7p9qhws.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I've now spent over 3 weeks of my life in Afghanistan, and I have barely told you about the AMAZING food that exists in this country!   In fact, I would honestly say that Afghanistan has some of the most underrated street food in the entire world.  All of the dishes here are so delicious, so plentiful and SO CHEAP!

In today's video, I take you on the streets of Bamiyan (in the central region of the country) to try some of the best Afghan street foods - IS ANYONE HUNGRY OUT THERE?! 

Please note that this video was extremely hard to edit because just 2 weeks after I left Bamiyan, there were 2 massive blasts that destroyed the main marketplace, leaving 14 people dead and dozens more wounded.  100% of this video was shot in that exact marketplace, which is now in ruins, and I am just devastated.  

In any regard, Bamiyan (and Afghanistan as a whole) is one of my favorite place on earth -- the culture is so raw and authentic, and the people are some of the most hospitable in the world!  I am loving every second of this trip and I can't wait to tell you more stories from the wonderful country of Afghanistan. 

PS - Would you try any of these Afghan dishes? Comment below!

-d1YrSGG5-w.title: The Destroyed 4th Century Buddhas of Afghanistan
-d1YrSGG5-w.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

DID YOU KNOW that a town called Bamiyan in Afghanistan marks the Westernmost expansion of Buddhism in the history of the world?

Way back in the 4th Century, people in Bamiyan carved two MASSIVE Buddha statues (literally) into the mountain and they stood strong for 1,600+ years, until they were ruthlessly destroyed by the Taliban in 2001...  It's one of the saddest stories known to mankind, but it was still an incredible site to visit!  

After spending 3 days in Bamiyan,  I am COMPLETELY AMAZED by the nature around this mountainous area, as well as the amazing people who have welcomed me here with open arms!  For decades, Bamiyan has been recognized as the safest and most stable place in the Afghanistan -- which certainly felt like the truth when I was there a few weeks ago... but then the horrible news came that 2 bomb blasts rocked the main marketplace -- where much of this video was shot. 

It breaks my heart that the innocent people of Afghanistan must risk their lives every time they step outside.  Afghanistan is one of my favorite countries in the world, and I hope that you guys have been enjoying this series on my second visit to the country.  I still have 4 more videos to share!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more stories from every country in the world, and come say hi on Instagram! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

aQHobu9EFKA.title: i visited the capital of the Taliban (Afghanistan)
aQHobu9EFKA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

TODAY’S STORY IN CRAZY! Welcome to Kandahar, Afghanistan. 

Kandahar is well known as being the headquarters of a Sunni Islamic political movement and military organization who is currently waging war within the country.    Since their uprising in the mid 1990s, Kandahar has been the home base where the group operates, and at one point in time (in the early 2000s), they controlled 95% of the country.

HI GUYS! I'm back in Iraqi Kurdistan with my friend Baderkhan - remember him? The guy who has been to 70+ countries with the World's Worst Passport (Iraq)?

I decided to make a sequel about his life because he is a such a good guy and has so many inspiring viewpoints and perspectives.

fAqgzRPQhxs.title: THE WHISTLE LANGUAGE (most unique language earth!)
fAqgzRPQhxs.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Would you believe me if I told you that somewhere in the mountains of  Turkey, there's a small village called Kuskoy where ALL of its residents can speak a language that is entirely made up of WHISTLES?  And every single word in the Turkish language can be translated into these unique sounds?

I recently visited Kuskoy and was completely blown away by how cool and unique this vernacular is!   You really have to hear it to believe it. 

As the locals told me, this whistle language was invented around 500 years ago by local farmers, who needed to communicate with their peers over the steep hills...  Amazingly, the whistles can be heard up to 3 kilometers away!!

Share this video with your friends if you enjoyed!

Follow @Drew Binsky for more travel stories from every country in the world, and join me on Instagram: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

As the locals told me, this whistle language was invented around 500 years ago by local farmers, who needed to communicate with their peers over the steep hills...  Amazingly, the whistles can be heard up to 3 kilometers away!!

Share this video with your friends if you enjoyed!

dxGmMybsIJc.title: This Ice Cream DOESN'T MELT (Turkish Ice Cream)
dxGmMybsIJc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

Any ice cream lovers out there?  Prepare to get your mind blown when you hear about Turkish ice cream! 

No matter where you go in this country, you can find men wearing traditional Turkish clothes, and serving fresh ice cream from a long metal stick inside of a deep bucket.  The consistency of the ice cream is incredibly thick, and it really does not melt!!!  Because of its thickness, the vendors will often play games with you when you try to buy ice cream, making you look like a fool on the streets in public. 

Today, I went to the city where Turkish ice cream was invented (Kahramanmaras) with one mission in mind -- to tell you the full story about how ice cream became such a popular thing in Turkey! 

Share this video if you love ice cream!

0qVQL_HQ3SI.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

If you've never heard of a Turkish Bath before, then prepare yourself for what you're about to see!  I've never felt cleaner before in my life, but the process to get clean is quite intimidating.

My first time doing a Turkish Bath was in 2012 in Istanbul, and all I can remember is an old, hairy Turkish man scrubbing down every millimeter of my body with sandpaper and soap...

I decided to do it again here in the Southeastern Turkish city of Mardin, and document the entire process so you can see what it's like.  

If you ever find yourself in Turkey, I high suggest giving a Turkish Bath a try!

VD7Vt5KZIXI.title: WHY IS EVERYTHING FREE IN TURKEY? (seriously!)
VD7Vt5KZIXI.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This video is NOT staged and this is NOT a joke!!

I arrived here in Gaziantep - the culinary capital of Turkey - and as I've been going eating different foods from street vendors, NOBODY IS LETTING ME PAY FOR ANYTHING!

Turkish people are so kind and generous that when they discover that I am a tourist, they simply will not accept my money.   In some cases, they aggressively hit my hand away and put my money back in my pocket. It's unbelievable. 

If you guys can remember about 1.5 years ago, I made a similar video in Peshawar, Pakistan -- where nobody would accept my payment -- so this is a kind of a sequel.   And now, I think you will finally start to understand that the people in this part of the world are the friendliest!

I hope this video inspires some of you to visit Turkey, it really is that amazing here.

oZtD8BNvUiQ.title: Why I'm at the SYRIAN BORDER
oZtD8BNvUiQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

We have made it to Southern Turkey, and I am instantly obsessed with this place!!  It contains everything I love about the world -- amazing hospitality, delicious food, mind-blowing history and beautiful ancient wonders. 

My friend Anil and I have been exploring the ins and outs of Antakya and the Hatay province, which reminds me a lot of Syria given it's close proximity. 

Some of you guys may remember that about 10 months ago, I spent 2 incredible weeks in Syria -- and considering that the border is just a 1 hour drive away, I had to spontaneously go there and see what I could discover.  My curiosity led the way. 

It ended up being a really special experience to spend time in the border town of Yayladagi, where I was fascinated at the mix of Turkish/Syrian culture.    

Here is the full story from today, I hope you enjoy!

JrLzhQA_yWQ.title: THE WORLD'S TALLEST MAN (251 cm, 8 feet 2 inches!)
JrLzhQA_yWQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

Today in South Eastern Turkey, I met Sultan Kösen -- AKA THE WORLD'S TALLEST MAN!!!

I first heard about Sultan in 2009, when he was awarded a Guinness World Record title for his astounding height of 251 centimeters, or 8 feet 2 inches -- that's almost 3 feet taller than me!

Even though Sultan is a giant on the outside, he's incredibly gentle, warm and friendly on the inside, and we were all laughing for the 3 hours we spent together.  

This was a very special video to make because Sultan invited us into his house, in a tiny village, where his parents (surprisingly) cooked us breakfast after the interview.    It was an amazing experience, and quite an emotional morning after hearing about some of the struggles than Sultan has been through in his life (i.e. needing to get multiple surgeries to stop his growth)...  But nowadays, he is as happy as can be! 

This is the full story of Sultan Kösen!

HALjUHkzdVw.title: THE DESERT WARRIORS (Bedouin Tribe)
HALjUHkzdVw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Growing up in Arizona, I've always been fascinated by the desert.  That's why I am particularly interested in the BEDOUIN TRIBE of North Africa and the Middle East.  Believe it or not, there are over 8 million bedouins (nomadic Arabs) living across 21 desert nations. 

Over the years, I have had some incredible experiences with bedouins in countries like Yemen, Oman, Sudan, Algeria, Mauritania, and Jordan — and today, I finally got around to telling you the story of the Bedouins while here in the Sinai peninsula of Egypt.

All I have to say is that bedouins are some of the most open and hospitable people on earth -- they will force-feed you and serve you copious amounts of hot sugary tea.   I really admire their lifestyles and I'm excited to share this story with you. 

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more stories from every country in the world: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

ddwvmqHnSSk.title: YOUR PERFUME GROWS HERE (60% of global supply)
ddwvmqHnSSk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Did you know that over HALF of the global supply of perfume comes from jasmine flowers in a small village in Northern Egypt?

The village is called Shubra Blula, and I came here today before sunrise to learn all about the process, which is fascinating! 

During the peak season (which is now), thousands of local residents spend their entire nights hand picking these beautiful white jasmine flowers directly from the plants.  Then, they are sent to a nearby factory to extract the liquid which is then sold to Paris, New York, Hong Kong and all around the world to be bottled up into perfume. 

Who knew that Egypt is the king of the perfume world?  I surely didn't before this trip! 

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more travel stories from every country: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Thank you @abdra_96 for the extra shots

jSvvZZ4TR5I.title: THE ORGANIC PHARMACIST (100% natural products)
jSvvZZ4TR5I.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

WOW!! I've spent the last 24 hours living with Dr. Ahmed Salah at his home in a remote part of the Sinai Peninsula in Egypt.  You guys are going to LOVE his story!!!

After getting inspired from meeting an Austrian tourist in his village 25 years ago, Dr. Ahmed has spent the last two decades educating himself on natural remedies to cure (almost) any kind of sickness.  He grows EVERYTHING himself in his backyard -- I'm talking about hundreds of plants, vegetables, fruits, herbs and spices -- and crafts these 100% natural products into care packages to sell in his beautiful pharmacy.   The craziest part about all of this is that we are in the middle of the desert!

Share this video with your friends if you feel inspired by Dr. Ahmed Salah -- I think the world could use a little bit of his positive energy these days.

yKp-_Mi5zsM.title: WHERE COVID DOESN'T EXIST... (Egypt)
yKp-_Mi5zsM.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I truly can't believe my eyes...  Here in Egypt, about 1% of people on the streets are wearing masks. Nobody is social distancing.  Many people are shaking hands, hugging, kissing and touching each other.  I see public gatherings everywhere -- weddings, parties, markets and concerts.   Even in Cairo airport and on domestic flights, I'm seeing the majority of people wrapping their masks around their chins. 

Of course Covid exists in Egypt -- the title of this video is deceiving.  But I am so shocked at how they do not take this pandemic seriously!!!

It's wild to see how different countries perceive Covid in different ways -- from Los Angeles to Cairo, they're polar opposites.  I'd love to hear your thoughts on this matter - please comment below and let's get a discussion started. 

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more stories from every country:
https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Thank you @abdra_96 for the drone shots!

p_tCpi3tHXQ.title: AFRICA'S HIDDEN TRIBE (they live with crocodiles)
p_tCpi3tHXQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I have arrived in a place called ASWAN, in the South of Egypt! Despite the fact that it's 47C outside (117F), it's SO AMAZING here because we are right on the Nile and everything is incredibly peaceful.

As we took a morning boat ride across the Nile, I noticed a really unique village on the shore, consisting of a bunch of blue and white circular buildings.  We spontaneously stopped, checked out the village, and I realized that it's home to the NUBIAN TRIBE (which if you can remember from my videos in Sudan last year, it's the same people!).

This story is all about the Nubian way of life (yes, they really have crocodiles in their living room). I hope you enjoy!

6lJLmw4_w4k.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Welcome back to the 41st episode of my $10 Series!  Today I take you around the bustling city of Cairo, Egypt to see how far I can stretch $10USD (PS: I got 10 items!).

I actually went to Cairo the first time in 2015 - way back when I was a budget backpacker and travel blogger (before I owned a video camera).  I was young and naïve and to be honest, I didn't have a great time here.  

But now, I'm back with fresh eyes and new perspectives, and let's just say that I'm enjoying Cairo about 10X as much as I did 5 years ago.  It's also a very special time to visit because there are (literally) ZERO TOURISTS HERE, so I had the Pyramids of Giza all to myself.   As long as you take precautions (wear mask, avoid physical contact, wash hands frequently), then traveling is possible right now amid this new normal. 

Have you ever been to Cairo?  Please comment below and tell me what are your favorite things to do in the city!

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram Stories for more updates from my trip.  I'll be going all over Egypt! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky.

5Am56XUAR_s.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Welcome to LEAVENWORTH, WASHINGTON -- I had no idea that this place existed until 3 days ago, but now I'm here and I'm loving what I'm seeing!!

Leavenworth is a small town of 2,000 residents tucked away in the beautiful Cascade mountains.   The entire town was modeled after a village in Bavaria (southern Germany) and to this day, it remains almost IDENTICAL to what you can find in Germany.  Everything from the architecture to the food, attire, beer, shopping, lifestyle and overall vibes -- it's basically like you are visiting Germany while in the USA!

Have you ever heard of this town before?  If not, then add it to your list because it's 100% worth it!

OuF19EAP9E0.title: COCA-COLA LIVES HERE (People Drink 2.2 Liters PER DAY)
OuF19EAP9E0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

I literally can't believe my eyes.  Here in Chiapas -- the Southernmost and poorest state of Mexico, the people drink on average 2.2 liters of Coca-Cola PER DAY.   That is more than any country in the WORLD per capita. 

In a state where there are massive shortages of both running/drinking water -- Coca-Cola is found in abundance and it's THE beverage of choice.   I'm telling you that it's seen everywhere, from popular restaurants to rural villages and small shops.  

But the most surprising thing to me was when I learned that Coca-Cola is viewed as spiritual to the Tzotzil indigenous people in Chiapas.  In a town called San Juan Chamula, coca-cola is deeply intertwined with their culture. It's used as an offering in their main place of worship.   They believe that coke can heal the sick, proving to be one of the most interesting rituals I've ever seen. 

As a result of all of this binge coke drinking, it's no surprise that diabetes is a becoming a huge problem and it's responsible for 3,000 death per year. 

I love Mexico so much, but this is an issue that I couldn't let slide.  Would love to get your thoughts on it. 

More travel stories on: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

#DrewBinsky #CocaCola #Mexico

ZcctJmQIrT8.title: THE JUNGLE TRIBE (Mexico's Most Remote Culture)
ZcctJmQIrT8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I've spent the past 72 hours living with Mexico's most remote indigenous tribe called the Lacandones, and it has been absolutely breathtaking!!!  I've been on such a high over the last 24 hours as I've been editing this video nonstop, and I think you will really enjoy it. 

There are less than 1,000 Lacandones remaining in 4 separate villages, all of which are deep in the Lacandon jungle in the state of Chiapas - about 10 miles from the Guatemalan border.   

They dress themselves in white as a symbol of peace, grow their hair out as long as possible and speak one of the world's most unique languages called Hach tʼan.

The Lacandons aren't always open to visitors, by my friend Diego and I were able to get special permission to observe their fascinating culture. 

This is the 5th tribe I've spent quality time with around the world and it's something I really love doing.  It's like hitting the 'refresh' button on life.  It allows me to see a different perspective on our existence and have a new appreciation for our beautiful planet. 

Thanks as always for watching!  Follow me on Facebook Drew Binsky for more travel stories from every country, and join me on Instagram! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky
