They dress themselves in white as a symbol of peace, grow their hair out as long as possible and speak one of the world's most unique languages called Hach tʼan.

The Lacandons aren't always open to visitors, by my friend Diego and I were able to get special permission to observe their fascinating culture. 

This is the 5th tribe I've spent quality time with around the world and it's something I really love doing.  It's like hitting the 'refresh' button on life.  It allows me to see a different perspective on our existence and have a new appreciation for our beautiful planet. 

Thanks as always for watching!  Follow me on Facebook Drew Binsky for more travel stories from every country, and join me on Instagram! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

It's my pleasure to tell you the story of a young man named José Luis, who has won numerous competitions to be named Mexico's Best Bartender. 

But this story is less about bartending, and more about how José Luis overcame adversity to get here. 

He was born and raised in one of Mexico City's most dangerous neighborhoods called Nezahualcóyotl.  Against all odds, he got a degree from a top university and went on to teach himself how to bartend (which was not easy to do in Mexico).  

Now, he has been to 31 countries and over 50 cities to bartend for people around the world and he's only getting started!  What an incredible guy and he is proof that anything is possible if you put your mind to it. PMbF_Kfp1j4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Have you ever heard of MEZCAL?  It's a Mexican liquor that is dubbed as "tequila's younger cousin," because it is also made from the same plant called agave.  

I came down to Oaxaca - the state where mezcal is produced -- and I am amazed by this production!  We met up with a mezcal farmer who gave us the whole experience...

I'm telling you right now that mezcal is about to take the world by storm (in the same way that tequila has) because it's so damn good!  

More stories to come soon from Oaxaca and Mexico!

CR21lR8lovw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Everyone has heard of the alcoholic beverage called TEQUILA, but did you know that it's actually the name of a lively town in MEXICO?!

...Either did I, until I came to the state of Jalisco and learned all about it!  The town of Tequila is everything you'd imagine it to be and more.  It's where the main production of tequila takes place in Mexico and the entire region is surrounded by blue agave plants - the main ingredient that the drink comes from. The landscape is so beautiful that it has been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

When thinking of Mexico, most people tend to think about Cancun or Cabo or Mexico City... but what about the second-most populated city called Guadalajara?  I decided to come here to see what it's all about, and I'm truly blown away by how awesome it is!

Guadalajara is the capital of the state of Jalisco, which is the origin of Mexico’s greatest traditions and products such as tequila, cowboys, cholula sauce, Santana and of course, mariachis.   In my opinion, this could be the best place to visit in the entire country.

a8K_Lsq4c3c.title: THE SILVER CITY (Taxco, Mexico)
a8K_Lsq4c3c.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

What a pleasant surprise!!!  I took a 3 hour road trip from Mexico City a lovely small town called Taxco, which looks like a fairy tale! 

There are so many things to enjoy about Taxco, but it's most famous for having the purest silver in all of Mexico.  

Mining here began in the pre-Hispanic period with natives extracting a stones for ritual purposes. Then the Spanish came along and discovered silver in the early 16th Century, and they started commercial mining in the area and built an amazing church in 1758 which still stands today.  Even though mining has stopped in the region, the town of Taxco has remarkably carried on its silver tradition.  The streets are filled with hundreds of shops, markets and open air venues selling all kinds of fine silver jewelry and they still make every piece by hand.

If you come to Mexico, don't miss out on Taxco!

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more content from every country in the world: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

The Middle East is my absolute favorite region in the world for many reasons, but none more than the hospitality.  I actually never knew that people could be so friendly until I ventured off into the mountains of Afghanistan, the valleys of Yemen, the villages of Syria and the small boutique shops of Iran. 

All I can say is that after spending 4+ months of my life traveling throughout the region, I can say that the Middle East is much safer and more beautiful than what the media makes it out to be! 

Join me in today's video where I show you how far I could spend $10 in Yemen, Syria, Afghanistan and Iran.  This is some of my all time favorite content, so I hope you enjoy watching it as much as I had fun making it!

cBjxDtAcHXU.title: REFUGEE TO SUPERMODEL (Halima Aden)
cBjxDtAcHXU.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Today I had the pleasure of spending an evening with Somali Supermodel Halima Aden.  If you haven't heard of her already, I know you will find her story extremely inspiring! 

Halima was born in a refugee camp in Kakuma, Kenya, because her family was forced to to flee Somalia due to the civil war in the early 1990s.  When she was 7 years old, her family migrated to the USA (Minnesota) where she found herself in a culture shock and couldn't speak English... But that never stopped her from finding her voice! 

Fast forward 11 years and not only did she become a semi-finalist at Miss Minnesota USA, but she was the FIRST PERSON in their 65 year history to wear a hijab and burkini on stage.  It wasn't intentional, it was just Halima staying true to herself and her beliefs -- but it essentially got the attention of the world and now she has been on the cover of Vogue Magazine, Allure, highlighted in Sports Illustrated Swimsuit Edition among dozens of others.  She travels all over the world doing photoshoots, being a UNICEF ambassador and collaborating with brands that she loves.   And the craziest part? She is only 22 years old! 


The sky is the limit for Halima as she continues to be a leader and role model for people in her community, and I can't wait to see what's next!

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more inspiring stories like this one! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

#HalimaAden #Somalia #Beauty

iRhv_NPP1hQ.title: SURPRISE SYRIAN MEAL (in South Dakota!)
iRhv_NPP1hQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

When I woke up this morning in South Dakota, the last thing I thought I'd be eating for lunch is a delicious plate of SYRIAN FOOD!

But much to my surprise, I received a message on Instagram from a lovely lady named Sanaa, who invited me for lunch at her restaurant --  one of the most popular Syrian places in the country. 

Words cannot express how happy this meal and experience made me!  I spent 2 weeks in Syria last November, and I've really been missing the incredible food and hospitality - and thankfully, I just got my fix of both.  Syrian cuisine might just be the best on this planet, what do you think?

If you ever come to Sioux Falls, South Dakota, make sure to stop by Sanaa's Restaurant and tell her that Drew says hi!

► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Have you ever heard of the Baháʼí Faith?  It's considered as the world's newest major religion, and it's absolutely fascinating to learn about. 

I actually first heard about the Baháʼí Faith 5 years ago when I stumbled upon a beautiful Baháʼí temple in Delhi, India -- and over the years as I've met more Baháʼís, I've become intrigued by their beliefs and way of life. 

In today's video, you will learn all about the Baháʼí Faith through exclusive interviews with Rainn Wilson, Steve Sarowitz and Radiance Talley -- three amazing Baháʼís who I've really enjoyed speaking with. 

Just out of curiosity - how many of you guys have heard about the  Baháʼí Faith before this video?  Do any of you guys agree with their beliefs?  Please comment below - I'd love to hear from you!

qzGOkg5BYQY.title: ESCAPING NORTH KOREA (to America)
qzGOkg5BYQY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

Today in Chicago, I had the pleasure to meet a young North Korean girl named Evelyn.   6 years ago, when she was 15 years old, she escaped North Korea with her mother for a better life.  Both without passports, they spent 1 month traveling by foot across China, Laos and Thailand - where the South Korean government officially recognized her as a refugee and she was granted permission to migrate to the United States of America. 

In this eye-opening interview, Evelyn tells me her escape story and how she has managed to integrate so well into American society.  She lives all by herself and just bought her first car (with her hard-earned income!).   

Follow Evelyn on YouTube to keep up with her life: https://bit.ly/32gO3O3

c_moHPpxXSQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

**I made this video 2.5 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

HELLO FROM THE SOUTHERN END OF THE WORLD -- Cape Horn, Chile!

Cape Horn is the second-to-last stop on our Hurtigruten Expedition (I really don't want this trip to end!). It's the Southernmost point in South America, and the place where the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans meet.

Cape Horn is widely considered to have the most dangerous seas for sailors to cross, as thousands of lives have been taken since it was first discovered in 1616 by Dutch explorers. The hazardous year-round weather produces strong ocean currents, gale force winds and massive waves... Not to mention, the remoteness of these islands, far away from any civilization, make it very difficult to escape or call for help in an emergency situation.

Most attempted landings to Cape Horn have failed because of the wind & rain, but today we got EXTREMELY lucky with sunshine and moderate winds. I was told that this day is 1 in 100 by some of our crew members who have been to Cape Horn dozens of times.

Have you ever heard about Cape Horn? It's a great place to add to your bucket list! Also Chile is awesome!

Music: Kevin MacLeod

#Chile #DrewBinsky #Travel

osI-w4Rzg_4.title: THEY GOT MARRIED IN A #BLM PROTEST
osI-w4Rzg_4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This is one of the most amazing stories I've ever had the pleasure of telling you!!!  

Meet Lara and Sam - two incredible people who fell in love and had a wedding scheduled for May 31, 2020.  Little did they know that we would be in the middle of a pandemic, so they arranged a beautiful marriage in front of their house in Los Angeles, California. 

Even more surreal was the timing -- during their wedding night was one of the largest protests for #BlackLivesMatter on the streets of L.A... So Lara and Sam (in full wedding attire) decided to take their celebration to the street with thousands of people cheering them on. 

You can't plan things like this.  They just happen.  I'm so happy that I was able to meet and tell their story, and I hope it can bring you happiness among these unpleasant days!

► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

ANYONE ELSE OBSESSED WITH ASIA?

The beautiful continent of Asia has 50 countries, and I have visited 49 of them (only missing Saudi Arabia!).   In fact, I have spent 80% of my time on the Asian continent since 2012, living in Korea, Vietnam, Thailand, Philippines and extensively traveling around to other nations. 

In this video, I randomly draw Asian countries from a hat and provide you with my best travel tips, advice and memories from each one.  This video is 100% spontaneous -- meaning that no ideas/scripts were pre-planned.  It feels good to freely speak my mind, and I hope that you learn a thing or two from watching this video! 

I spent 3 days editing this one (mostly going through my old hardrives), so if you enjoyed, it would mean the world to me if you shared it with your friends!  I think we could all use a little travel inspiration these days while we're stuck at home...

ZcfhTKEZcGw.title: A LAYOVER IN BEIJING 🇨🇳
ZcfhTKEZcGw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

**I made this video 3 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

Let's talk about long layovers!

In my opinion (from years of travel experience), I can tell you that long layovers are THE BEST way to break up long travel days and have the chance to explore a new city for cheap.  I've had great experiences on long layovers in cities such as Istanbul, Doha, Dubai, Tokyo, Frankfurt, Addis Ababa, Nairobi and tons more! 

Did you know that at most major cities in China, you can get a FREE 72 hour transit visa if you have proof of an onwards flight? It's a great way to save the time & stress of applying for a Chinese visa.

This video documents my recent 18 hour layover in Beijing, as well as gives travel tips if you do the same.

In which city is your most memorable experience on a long layover?

HnCd98BdzA0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

**I made this video 2.5 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

Hi guys! I finished my second trip to HA LONG BAY - the mystical place where 1,969 limestone islands are scattered around a giant bay in Northeastern Vietnam. It's one of the 7 Wonders of the World, a UNESCO site, and in my opinion, the top 5 most stunning displays of nature on our planet.

In this video, I take you around Ha Long Bay (with my brand new Panasonic Lumix GH!) and teach you some interesting facts about what I've discovered.

Do me a favor and add Ha Long Bay to your bucket list if you haven't been already -- You can take a 2 day/1 night all-inclusive trip from Hanoi for as cheap as $40 per person.

#DrewBinsky #Vietnam #Asia

gxrfMGLjpLE.title: SAFEST CITY IN MIDDLE EAST? (Amman, Jordan)
gxrfMGLjpLE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

**I made this video 3 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

IT'S ALL SMILES HERE FROM AMMAN, JORDAN 🇯🇴 

Today was fantastic. We toured all around Amman -- visited ruins and museums, learned about the ancient history, ate lots of hummus and falafel, and I hosted a meet up with lots of likeminded travelers!  There is no doubt in my mind that this is the safest city in the Middle East.  Heck, it's safer than anywhere I've been in the USA!

Also, I literally haven't slept a wink in 35 hours since leaving Manila and spending all last night editing videos in the Dubai airport... I'M COMPLETELY DEAD. Especially after editing this video. My brain hurts. Going to sleep now, and gotta wake up at 6AM to visit Petra!

Has anyone else been to Amman, Jordan, and can back me up on the fact that it's extremely safe?  I want to hear from you in the comments below!

P.S. - I love the Middle East ❤️ Every time I come here, I am overwhelmed by how welcoming and friendly the people are. I've never experienced hospitality like this in any other part of the world. 

#DrewBinsky #Amman #Jordan

**I made this video 3 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

HAVE YOU EVER HEARD OF JOLLIBEE, or seen the dazzling red bee mascot in your country?

If not, then find out why Filipinos are going ABSOLUTELY CRAZY over this unique fast-food chain.  In the Philippines, Jollibee is way more popular than McDonald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendys or any other fast food chain you can think of.  They have the strangest menu items, such as a sweet spaghetti with red hot dogs and a pineapple burger, but I will have to admit that Jollibee hits the spot every time.  It's on every corner in the Philippines (and in over 30 countries around the world).  You have to give it a try if you ever pass by one!

pOlP5gxFE80.title: 7-ELEVEN is CRAZY in JAPAN
pOlP5gxFE80.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

**I made this video 3 years ago, but only shared it to Facebook...so I wanted to post it for all you guys here on YouTube!  Please excuse the fast paced editing and shaky camera -- I was a newbie back then**

You've never experienced 7-Eleven until you've been to Japan... Seriously, they put the "convenience" in convenience store and it will blow your mind what you can find inside. 

7-Eleven, which is actually co-owned by the Japanese, has MUCH more than just snacks, drinks and slurpees (in fact, slurpees don't even exist here!) 7-Eleven in Japan is almost like a mini Walmart -- a one-stop-shop for anything you could possibly need on the go. And believe it or not, 7-Eleven is Japan's #1 food product retailer, with a large assortment of fresh and tasty meals!!

In this video, I explore the ins and outs of 7-Eleven in Japan, and why I think it's so amazing. Does anyone else agree with me? I think it's just one of those things where, "if you've been, then you know..."

Music: Kevin MacLeod

Today I had the absolute pleasure of meeting Leon Logothetis, someone  I've looked up to for quite some time after seeing his popular Netflix show called "The Kindness Diaries."

Just as the title of his show suggests, Leon travels around the world relying on the kindness of strangers.  I didn't mention in the video, but he has visited over 100 countries -- and you won't believe some of the touching stories he has to tell.  

I've always said that 99.9% of the people in the world are kind and hospitable, and Leon's adventures are a strong testament that this is true.  I can't wait to meet Leon again and travel with him sometime in the near future -- we will make a great team, don't you think?!

cvf7POmZz5E.title: MY UNFORTUNATE BIRTHDAY (thoughts on turning 29)
cvf7POmZz5E.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Today is my 29th birthday, and it's certainly one for the record books... 

In late March, I was certain that I'd be on a 9-week trip visiting my final 6 countries, while filming a 90-minute documentary along the way.  I was supposed to be in Palau in this very moment.

Well, clearly, that isn't happening... yet.  I'm stuck right now in L.A. and I have no idea when I'll be on the road again.  That is a very scary sentence to say. 

In today's video, I set down my camera and spoke my thoughts for 9 minutes straight.  

Thank you in advance for the birthday wishes, and more importantly, I want to thank YOU for all of your support over the years.  Without you guys, I would probably be working a 9-5 somewhere and even more depressed with life at the moment.  

We will get through this mess.  It will end.  Life, as we knew it, will return.  We must keep these positive thoughts and affirmations going in our heads.    

Thanks for listening.  Wash your hands.  Stay 6 feet apart. Love you all and have a great day!

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram more (happier) travel stories: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

55e5v5EjIJE.title: 3 ISLAMIC STORIES
55e5v5EjIJE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

RAMADAN MUBARAK to all of my Muslim brothers and sisters out there!

As a Jewish traveler, you might find it shocking to hear that I have a deep love and appreciation for the Islamic world.  After all, the world about 26% of the world is Muslim, so if you are going to every country, then you will spend your fair share being immersed in the religion. 

In today's video, I want to bring back 3 special stories about Islam that I've discovered on my travels.  The first one is about how my friend Sal, who I recently met in Senegal, reverted to Islam -- the second one is about spending Ramadan in the Maldives -- and the third is about how converting to Islam saved a young French girl named Justine.

Does Islam play a role in your life?  If so, I'd love to hear it in the comments below!

GIwlLEWqMGk.title: WORLD'S EMPTIEST COUNTRIES
GIwlLEWqMGk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Most of the time you'll see me traveling in densely-populated countries like Singapore or Pakistan or South Korea -- but that doesn't mean I don't enjoy getting out in nature!  The truth is that even with a global population of 7.6 billion, our world is filled with remote places which are fascinating to visit.  In a sense, they are my escape from reality.  

In today's video, we learn about some of the world's emptiest countries per capita:  NAMIBIA, MONGOLIA, GREENLAND, AUSTRALIA, SURINAME.

In some of these countries, you will find an average of 1 or 2 people living per square kilometer -- now that sounds like a great escape, (especially these days) -- doesn't it?!

Have you been to any of these countries before?

FiLrAMVageA.title: NORTH KOREA vs. SOUTH KOREA (What's the Difference?)
FiLrAMVageA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I spent 2 years living and teaching English in South Korea -- it was one of the best decisions of my life!  After getting hooked on the delicious food, vibrant life and modern culture of Seoul -- I was really curious to see what life is like North of the border...

So exactly 3 years ago, I took a trip to Pyongyang, North Korea for 3 days (I'm one of the last Americans to step foot on North Korean soil).  I made a video there -- one of my first ever --  and it currently has over 17 million views.  

But what is life really like in both Koreas?  Are they more similar, or different?  The answer is a little of both -- so join me in today's video as I compare and contrast North Korea with South Korea. 

What are your thoughts?  Have you ever been to either North or South Korea? Would love to hear from you in the comments below!

RIIZ5CZx1Ms.title: HOW I FIND PEACE ⛳
RIIZ5CZx1Ms.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

When I am traveling the world, which I have been doing nonstop since August 2012, I am constantly stressed... The long layovers, unexpected delays, dangerous situations, difficulties of getting visas and daunting immigration checks ALL WHILE creating videos every day has led me to have severe anxiety.

But there is one way that I temporarily cure my anxiety, and that is by playing the sport of golf. I've played rounds in 42 countries -- from Vanuatu to Burundi to Guyana -- and it's the only time to relax my mind.

I realize that golf is likely a boring subject for you if you do not play, and that's why I hardly ever speak about it. I never want to bore you! But the truth is that this sport has played a huge part of my life since I was 12 and
I always wanted to be a professional golfer. In today's video, I want to open up and share how golf has helped keep me sane amid this stressful lifestyle on the road.

For all of you workaholics out there, I urge you to find a sport, game, hobby or skill that you can practice to keep your mind healthy. It will make a tremendous difference in your life - I promise!

Any other golfers out there? Would love to know who you are!

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for more unique stories like this one! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

#DrewBinsky #Golf #Travel

What is happening right now? Should you stop traveling?  Is life cancelled?

The world is in pieces right now.  The coronavirus has infected over 150,000 people in 151 countries, taking the lives of 5,800 innocent people.   

In this video, I share with you my thoughts, reactions and suggestions for how to live through this horrible pandemic, as well as how you should approach travel right now.    

To sum it up:  Don't travel, stay home, wash your hands with soap 10X a day and try to stay away from crowded places.   There are many unknowns right now, but if one thing's for sure, it's that human beings are resilient.  We will get through this together -- how long it takes is up to our cooperation.    

I will admit that my stance on COVID-19 has changed.  From the beginning of the breakout (January), I have been on the road traveling.  While it hasn't disrupted my travel plans, I have now realized the seriousness of this pandemic and we need to take it seriously.   Luckily, I am home with my family and friends now in Arizona, and I will not be moving for (at least) several weeks. 

I would love nothing more than to hear your opinions on coronavirus -- how has your life changed?  Have you personally been affected by it?  What do you think the future holds?

gLynmh_VJIo.title: THE TATTOO LADY
gLynmh_VJIo.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I've spent the last 24 hours living with the Embera tribe of Southern Panama, and the most fascinating things about this experience has been learning about their tattoo culture.   

They have this local fruit called JAGUA, which only grows on select trees in Central/South America.   The Emberas extract black juice from the fruit and use it as an ink that they paint their bodies with, and it stays active for about 2 weeks.   The geometric shapes and designs have been passed down from their ancestors, and they use it today as a sunscreen and shampoo as well.

This lady, named Lisa, is the main tattoo artist in her community of 24 families and so I wanted to make a story on her life because I find it to be incredible!

Anyone out there have a love for tattoos?   Please do share in the comments below!

OMG GUYS, I SERIOUSLY FOUND PARADISE in the Dominican Republic, and NO, it's not in Punta Cana or La Romana!

It's called Samaná -- a peninsula way up in the North Eastern part of the country, home of 110,000 smiling faces and 6 MILLION palm trees.  That's approximately 54 palm trees for every 1 resident. 

I am really impressed by what I'm experiencing up here in Samaná.  I've been to 190 countries and this is one of the most outstanding places in the world for pristine nature, awesome adventure and just life in general.  Do me a favor and visit Samaná if you ever find yourself in the Dominican Republic, you won't regret it!

Special thanks Go Dominican Republic for helping make this trip possible, and to "That Jungle Life" for the extra footage.

fr7KJ39goNs.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I just spent the most incredible day with the most inspiring dude in Samaná, Dominican Republic.  His name is Bartolo, AKA the Tree House Dude, because he made his childhood dreams come true by building the most epic Tree House Village in the middle of the jungle.   You have to see it to believe it!

It wasn't always easy for Bartolo, as he grew up in a very poor household in Boise, Idaho.  To pay for his college, which took him 13 years to complete, he was scrubbing toilets and running a commercial cleaning company...  Then when he graduated, he went on vacation in the Dominican Republic, where he found his "true calling" as he says, and he has never left since then. 

Here is the full story of Bartolo.  If you ever go to the Dominican Republic, then do me a favor and stay at the Dominican Tree House Village!

localized.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I just spent the most incredible day with the most inspiring dude in Samaná, Dominican Republic.  His name is Bartolo, AKA the Tree House Dude, because he made his childhood dreams come true by building the most epic Tree House Village in the middle of the jungle.   You have to see it to believe it!

It wasn't always easy for Bartolo, as he grew up in a very poor household in Boise, Idaho.  To pay for his college, which took him 13 years to complete, he was scrubbing toilets and running a commercial cleaning company...  Then when he graduated, he went on vacation in the Dominican Republic, where he found his "true calling" as he says, and he has never left since then. 

Here is the full story of Bartolo.  If you ever go to the Dominican Republic, then do me a favor and stay at the Dominican Tree House Village!

Special thanks to "That Jungle Life" for the extra footage.

NFkBc-8LkI4.title: THE LAND OF BASEBALL ⚾️(Dominican Republic)
NFkBc-8LkI4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

The DOMINICAN REPUBLIC and BASEBALL go together like peanut butter and jelly.   It is (by far) the most popular sport in the country, and they have sent more players to the big leagues than any other country besides the United States.   That is beyond impressive for a country of just 11 million!

Baseball is seen as a gateway for many families to escape poverty, as teenagers as young as 16 years old have the chance to sign multi-million-dollar contracts.   

Each one of the 30 MLB teams have a baseball academy in the D.R., and I was lucky enough to be invited to the Arizona Diamondbacks facility and was very impressed by the talent of these young kids.  

As a former baseball player and huge fan, I truly had a blast shooting this video over the last few days around the Dominican Republic and I hope you enjoy watching!!

yHkyNEFIKG8.title: DREW BINSKY DOCUMENTARY (Border 197: Coming Soon)
yHkyNEFIKG8.description:
ANNOUNCEMENT!! 

I am thrilled to tell you that I will be making a 90 minute documentary called BORDER 197,  which will be filmed from May 15 to mid-July during my final 6 countries of Palau, Saudi Arabia, Ghana, Ecuador, Venezuela and Jamaica.  

This is a project that I've been wanting to create for 4 years, since I knew I was going to every country, and after pitching it around to some of the best documentary filmmakers, I teamed up with an awesome guy named Chris Wedding.  He and another top-line cinematographer will be traveling with me as become one of the youngest people in history to visit every country.  

This documentary will NOT be anything like my daily travel videos, nor a compilation of my travels.  You've already seen that through my videos. 

Instead, the film will take you behind the scenes of what it's really like to visit every country.  It will be personal.  You will hear from my family and close friends.   It will discuss things that I don't ever tell you, like my severe anxiety.  It will reflect on my biggest realizations/takeaways from crossing 197 borders.  We will discuss how dedicated I am to work 15 hour days, 7 days a week for 3 straight years to create these videos, which have amassed 1.2 billion views.  We will talk about how social media has not only allowed me to finance my trips, but it has let me connect with amazing locals (YOU GUYS) -- and how I rely on their generosity to introduce me to their homeland.  We will dive deep into this 'every country' culture, as there are only ~ 200 people who have done it.  And TONS more!

If you want to stay up to date on our project, please follow us on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinskydocumentary

Chris will be sharing a lot of BTS on his Instagram as well: www.instagram.com/look_see_do

I will be investing a lot of my time, energy and money into this project throughout 2020, and I couldn't be more excited to share it with you!

THANK YOU!!

vUueLb7CSII.title: The PROBLEM with MYANMAR... (no seat belts)
vUueLb7CSII.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I've never told this story publicly, but now is the time to share.  The last time I came to Myanmar (5 years ago), I became really good friends with a local tour operator named Sai, who sponsored my trip in exchange for a blog post (back when I used to be a blogger). 

The post I wrote went viral, and gave him a lot of new clients which he was really thankful for.  We remained close friends until I got a devastating email several years ago from a lady (who was on a tour with Sai after reading my blog post).  She told me that Sai got in a car crash and passed away.  He was not wearing a seat belt. 

This memory has haunted me for a long time.  Every time I came across the word "Myanmar," I instantly thought about Sai.  

And now I'm back here, and enjoying my trip overall... but I can't help but notice the unsafe situation these streets.  I took 4 taxis over the last few days and all 4 didn't have seat belts in the back seat.  To make matters even more frightening, many drivers on the streets of Yangon are reckless and I was terrified as I sat in the back seat without a seat belt on. 

I hope the government of Myanmar sees this video and does something to implement a change.  We've already lost Sai, and I hope that nobody else passes away from something that is easily preventable. 

That's all I want to say.  I do love Myanmar and I will certainly be back again someday, hopefully when I will feel safer getting around town.

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG for more travel stories.  https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

kaFXbN56ncw.title: LAND OF 10,000 TEMPLES (Bagan, Myanmar)
kaFXbN56ncw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This is a video about one of the most spectacular places on planet earth.  It's a place called BAGAN in the Central part of MYANMAR.  I  came here once 5 years ago, and I am still blown away by what I am seeing!

In short, there were over 10,000 temples and pagodas built in Bagan between the 9th and 13th Centuries, and it was a center for Buddhism worship in South East Asia.  Today, about 2,700 of these temples remain, ALL IN ORIGINAL FORM, and they are scattered around an area that's 13 kilometers by 8 kilometers large.  It's the biggest UNESCO archeological site in the world.  

In my opinion, Bagan is 10X more enjoyable than the Angkor region of Cambodia because there's much less tourists here and you can freely roam around on your own to have these magnificent temples all to your self.  

Oh yeah, and I forgot to mention that every morning in Bagan is like a hot air balloon festival!  I highly recommend adding Bagan to the very top of your bucket list, and I promise you it won't disappoint!

Has anyone out there been to Bagan?  Can you back up my thoughts on how amazing it is?

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG Stories right now to see life here unfold behind the scenes: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

hPrOyeOjrV0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Perhaps the most noticeable (and beautiful) thing about the culture of Burma (Myanmar) is the white/yellow paste on people's faces -- mostly women and children -- and it's seen everywhere!

This magical stuff is called THANAKA and it's been around in Burmese culture for over 2,000 years.   It's essentially a natural paste that is derived from a very specific tree bark, and it really enhances the beauty of the people here!

Have you ever heard of thanaka before?  This is one of the MANY reasons why you should add Myanmar to the top of your bucket list -- this country is truly amazing inside and out! 🇲🇲🇲🇲

BPrCt2cAXIE.title: MYANMAR HAS CHANGED 🇲🇲(so happy to be back!!!)
BPrCt2cAXIE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

HAPPY VALENTINE'S DAY FROM MYANMAR! ❤️

I'm so happy that I FINALLY made it back to Myanmar after 5 loooong years, and I am shocked my how much this country has evolved.   

5 years ago, there weren't any ATM machines and now there's about 10 on every street.  5 years ago there was a huge shortage in hotels, and now there are hundreds to choose from.  5 years ago the domestic airport was a tiny shack and now it's as modern and glorious as the one in Bangkok.  

All I can say is that I am thrilled to be back in this incredible country, and I hope you're ready to hear some of Asia's most unique stories here over the coming 5 days!

_-BgsV-Xgmo.title: World's Tallest & Smallest People (are neighbors!)
_-BgsV-Xgmo.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

DID YOU KNOW that the world's tallest people (Dinka tribe of South Sudan) are living directly across the border from the world's shortest people (Pygmy tribe of Central African Republic?)

I find this to be one of the most fascinating things in all of mankind! 

I have been lucky enough to visit both groups of people over the last few months, and I wanted to share with you how fascinating it is that they are literally neighbors!

In many situations around the world, whenever you hop over a border, you'll find the culture/traditions/language/people to be quite similar, but in Central Africa, it's a totally different world!

This video proves that Africa is, unquestionably, the most diverse continent on earth, with so many unique stories to tell.  I can't wait to go back again soon!

There is something really special about CENTRAL ASIA, and I wanted to make a video sharing my love for this region because it's often overlooked.  

The countries that make up Central Asia are Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan and sometimes Afghanistan is included as well.   Without question, you can find some of the most ancient history, most hospitable people and the cheapest prices on this planet!

Have you ever been to Central Asia? If not, then add this region to your bucket list because it's just about as good as it gets :)

► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

The most popular question I get is how, "Drew, How can you afford to travel?" --  so in this video, I give you a complete breakdown of how I've made money to afford my trips to 189 countries. 

No, I am not rich and no, I don't take money from my parents.  

I pay for all of my travel expenses out of money that I earned from hard work, and it has involved A LOT of pivoting to whatever is currently working out for me at the time  (teaching English -- travel blogging -- Snapchat -- Instagram -- Video making  -- ???)

In the second half of this video, I give you tons of tips and advice for how YOU can find jobs abroad (or remotely) to essentially travel for free. If you have any to add, please comment them below! 

This is meant to be an inspirational video, so I hope it triggers some of you to realize how many opportunities are out there because YOU CAN do this too, if you choose!   All you need is a wifi signal, a computer and a little bit of courage :)

voOCSj4OF9M.title: ASIA'S LATIN TOWN (they speak Spanish here!)
voOCSj4OF9M.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

After many years, I finally made it to down to ZAMBOANGA, a lovely town in the very South Western corner of the Philippines! 

Believe it or not, they speak SPANISH here!  Well, it's not 100% Spanish, it's called Chabacano which is more of a creole (mixed) dialect that developed when the Spaniards settled here almost 500 years ago.  

Not surprisingly, Zamboanga is dubbed as "Asia's Latin Town" for its strong roots to Spanish culture that can be seen not only in the language, but also in the cuisine and lifestyle.  

I've had a GREAT time here so far and I hope this video opens your eyes to a lesser-known part of the Philippines -- my favorite country in the world.

I've had a GREAT time here so far and I hope this video opens your eyes to a lesser-known part of the Philippines -- my favorite country in the world.

Deanna comes from a small town in the Philippines and was raised Catholic.  I am from a big city in the USA and was raised Jewish.  

Despite coming from totally different backgrounds on opposite ends of the world, we've been happily together for 4.5 and traveled to over 60 countries together!

But behind the scenes of our interracial relationship, we receive a fair amount of backlash and negative comments...   mostly from people who make inaccurate judgements about our lives.   

So we decided to make this video in retaliation to all the haters, explaining our take (i.e. the amazing benefits!) of being in an interracial relationship.

6OHuzgO8DCg.title: How FILIPINO is HONG KONG? (Domestic Helpers)
6OHuzgO8DCg.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

If you've never been to Hong Kong, then you may never realize how many Filipinos are living here -- over 130,000 of them in total!

The vast majority of them are middle age Filipina women who are working here as domestic helpers.  The reason they come here is because they are able to earn 10X the salary as back home for the same job.  They are some of the most unselfish people you will ever meet because they make huge sacrifices to live here, like not being with their family and not keeping any of their hard-earned income for themselves. 

But nonetheless, they always put a smile on their face and will just warm your heart to be around!  Here is the fill story of Filipino domestic helpers of Hong Kong.

mqG3F5kZFd0.title: THE MAN OF MOGADISHU (why he never left)
mqG3F5kZFd0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Today I have the pleasure of introducing you to Bashir Osman, who in my opinion, is THE man of Mogadishu.  He is the owner of the hotel I am staying at, called Peace Hotel, and the reason why I find his story to be so inspiring is because he has never left his home to live elsewhere.

xZZ6L4hJfKw.title: WHAT IT'S LIKE VISITING SOMALIA (Mogadishu)
xZZ6L4hJfKw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I can't believe I'm in Somalia's capital of Mogadishu.  It has essentially been the most dangerous city in the world for the last 3 decades, due to the ongoing Civil War which began started in 1991.  Tourism is almost nonexistent, and if you do come, then you must take precautions and follow the rules given to you at all times. 

BUT once I have looked past all the military checkpoints and I've gotten over my initial anxiety of being here, I am seeing an amazing culture with some of the kindest people I've ever met.   And shall we  talk about the beaches?  Somalia has the longest coastline in Africa with some of the most stunning coastlines I've ever seen! 

I won't say anything further, as I'll let the video speak for itself.  If you've ever been Mogadishu or Somalia, or are considering going there, then please comment below and we can get some conversation started.

eFUUrCXbvLE.title: World's MOST TRAVELED MAN? (Lee Abbamonte)
eFUUrCXbvLE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/
► Lee's Insta: https://www.instagram.com/leeabbamonte/

This is the inspiring story of my great friend Lee Abbamonte, who has just flown out from NYC to meet me here in Ethiopia.  We are heading to Somalia, next!

Lee is one of the world's most traveled people.  He has been to every U.N. member state, U.S. state, U.S. national park, both the North and South poles, and 321 unique territories overall.  

He finished all of the countries in 2011, about 9 years before I will do it, and those 9 years made a lot of difference in terms of how we each approached this mission.  In short, Lee wasn't able to leverage social media to lower his travel costs and get paid to travel...  because it wasn't popular back then.  Instead, he had to work and save his own money the old fashioned way -- making the journey significantly more expensive than what it's costing me.    He actually started his travels before the internet took off, back in 1998!

I hope you enjoy hearing Lee's story as he's a great friend and mentor.  We are both about to go on one of the craziest trips of our lives to Mogadishu, Somalia tomorrow -- so stay tuned!

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG STORIES for more! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

EN_VQoa1tb8.title: The Forgotten JEWS of ETHIOPIA
EN_VQoa1tb8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I'm back in Ethiopia for the 3rd time because it's one of my favorite countries in Africa!  I am now exploring a city in the North called Gondar, and little did I know that I'd come across thousands of fellow Jews.  

As you might know by now, I enjoy connecting with Jewish communities around the world, like I've done in Afghanistan, Yemen, Turkmenistan, Georgia, Philippines among many others  -- but this experience has been the most eye-opening because of how alive the Jewish culture is.  Some 4,000 Ethiopian Jews are here, studying torah, keeping Shabbat and learning Hebrew.  

If this is not a fascinating story, then I am not sure what is!  Join me as I take you inside the world of the forgotten Jewish tribe of Ethiopia.

Xqk68jzzNuA.title: 3 FRIENDS, 3 RELIGIONS (Jew + Muslim + Christian)
Xqk68jzzNuA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

The last 4 days of my life in Central African Republic have been spent with David, who is a Christian, and Fore, who is a Muslim.  I am Jewish. 

These guys are some of the best local hosts and friends I've made around the world.  Despite having 3 separate religions, it never held us back from getting along.  In fact, just the opposite happened -- we became curious about one another's beliefs and we had many great conversations.  Especially right now, in the midst of the holiday season!

There is a bigger message here that I hope you can all realize.  All 7 billion human beings on this planet should not be divided by our beliefs.   When it comes down to it, we are all the exact same. 

Thank you David and Fore for showing me an incredible time in your country, which my country's government currently issues the following travel advisory: Do not travel to Central African Republic (CAR) due to crime, civil unrest, and kidnapping.

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG STORIES for more from Central African Republic and beyond. Only 10 countries left! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Q_ndHZ5Mb2U.title: WORLD'S SHORTEST TRIBE (Pygmies of Central Africa)
Q_ndHZ5Mb2U.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This is the hardest I've ever worked to find, plan and execute a story in terms of logistics, finances and production.  It took me 2 months to plan and 35 hours to edit.  It's also the longest video I've ever made, at 15 minutes, and I really hope you watch it all because I love this kind of storytelling.   It's the reason why I travel. 

The pygmies are a group of tribal ethnicities native to Central Africa (Gabon, Cameroon, DRC and Central African Republic).  About 900,000 of them in total are entirely dependent on the dense forest for survival.  Genetically speaking, they are the world's shortest ethnic group for unknown reasons.  

I just spent 24 hours with them here in a remote part of Central African Republic and I made this story from my experience.  Please note that I had full permission from the chief to make this story and he was very happy that I came, as you'll hear about in the interview after the credits. 

If you find this story interesting, please share it with your friends!   I also welcome your comments, thoughts and feedback.  HAPPY NEW YEAR EVERYONE :)

_xVTRtXXkqA.title: World's BEST DRUMMERS (Burundi) 🇧🇮
_xVTRtXXkqA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This is one of my favorite stories that I've ever told you!! 

Welcome to BURUNDI, country #186.  This East African nation is overshadowed in many ways by its neighbors of Rwanda, Tanzania, DRC and Uganda -- but there is SO MUCH life happening on these streets, nothing more impressive than their insane drumming skills!

Today, I drove 3 hours from the capital of Bujumbura to a small village called Gishora to witness the drumming culture where it all started.  In fact, they claim to have invented the drum here way back in the day (made of wood and cow skin), and they are expert drummers to this day.  It's a full production of dancing, singing and ... carrying drums on their heads?  It's much harder than it looks! 

Here is the full story, which I hope you enjoy -- I stayed up all night editing this one cuz I am so excited to share :)  

This is Africa at it's finest.

7QKflbl48Hk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

What an incredible experience that was! I just attended a local wedding in the Democratic Republic of Congo 🇨🇩 It was fascinating to observe how the Congolese celebrate marriage -- there is no shortage of dancing, eating and smiling faces all around.

At first I was (very) intimidated being the only foreigner out of some 800 people in attendance, but they all welcomed me in with open arms and it turned out to be just fine. 

Have you ever attended a wedding in a foreign country?  It might be the best way to experience any given culture on earth!

jg1-hGiZ1aE.title: What is a CHUKUDU? (Goma, Congo)
jg1-hGiZ1aE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

All over the city of Goma in Eastern Congo, I've been seeing these unique two-wheeled handmade bicycles made of wood.  

They're called chukudus, and I learned that they're a major way that people transport goods around town. 

The kicker?  There is no engine or pedals! 

Given that Goma is so hilly, chukudus simply rolls down the hills and then you need to manually push it up.  Every single time.

It's a fascinating part of Goma's culture and I wanted to share it with you  in today's video!

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG Stories for more from the DRC! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

Cxs1ofRP3jk.title: World's Largest Primate (MOUNTAIN GORILLAS) 🦍🇨🇩
Cxs1ofRP3jk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

TODAY WAS AN AMAZING EXPERIENCE IN THE DR CONGO!!

I went trekking in the middle of the Congolese rainforest (Virunga National Park) to witness the incredible mountain gorillas in their natural habitat.  If you can remember about 2 years ago, I did something similar in Uganda, but to be honest, it's 10X better in the DRC because we were the only ones here in this remote setting.   I just can’t believe how human-like they are!

In other positive news, the world population of mountain gorillas has risen from about 600 to over 1,000 in the last decade, moving them from "critically endangered" to just "endangered." 

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG STORIES for more: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

P.S. Thank you so much to my friend Obed from Kumbu Kumbu tours for arranging this trip!  Follow him on Instagram to help plan your trip here: https://www.instagram.com/kumbukumbtours/

rrAH77K9w-A.title: She Gives Happiness (Tripoli, Libya)
rrAH77K9w-A.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

On the streets of Tripoli, Libya, I met a wonderful lady named Hadia who has a really inspiring story to share.

She's an entrepreneur, an artist, a teacher, a problem solver (among many others)  -- but the most encouraging thing about her story is how she is able to make everyone around her stay positive as Libya has been undergoing a tough state of war and instability.   

I was invited to her house/workshop today on the outskirts of Tripoli, where the majority of this video was shot.  It has been great getting a glimpse of her life and seeing how she is making an impact on Libyan society.

Ab4x_op5TP4.title: INSANE CASTLE of SYRIA (Krak des Chevaliers)
Ab4x_op5TP4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

WOAHHH!  I am so impressed by what I experienced today in Syria!  

Welcome to the Krak des Chevaliers -- it's considered as the world's most preserved medieval castle that sits in the South Western region of the country near Homs. 

It was built almost exactly 1,000 years ago, and despite being damaged a few years ago in the Syrian Civil War, it remains remarkably in tact.  It was a pleasure to explore the ins and outs of this castle today -- I was the only tourist here! 

The historical landmarks are just one of the MANY reasons why I have fallen in love with this Middle Eastern country.  Stay tuned for my last video in Syria tomorrow -- I saved the best for last!

SAvgcJE7Lvc.title: World's FRIENDLIEST Taxi Drivers?... (SYRIA)
SAvgcJE7Lvc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I've taken taxi rides in over 170 countries, and I have never EVER experienced more friendly drivers than here in Syria!  Seriously guys - I can't make this stuff up!  

Riding in a taxi in Syria is like being invited into someone's home for an amazing experience.  They offer you tea, candy and anything else they have in the car.  And most importantly, they smile at you and make you feel safe and comfortable!   

Also in this video, I didn't mention how CHEAP they are.  A 30 minute ride across the city is around $2USD.  Not a bad deal if you ask me!

If you're still reading this, I'd just like to extend an extra thank you to everyone who has watched, liked, commented and engaged in my Syria videos so far.  It's been incredible to experience this culture and hospitality first-hand.  It's one of my favorites in the world! More to come tomorrow.

-6cb_fPJWd0.title: THE BEST SYRIAN FOOD (Home Cooked Meal)
-6cb_fPJWd0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Yesterday, I was invited into a Syrian home which turned out to be THE BEST HOME COOKED MEAL that I've had in a loooong long time.   

The dish they made me is called kibbeh, and I think it's now my #1 favorite dish in the Middle East (behind shawarma and manaeesh).

I spent 5 hours with this amazing family as we went to the market to get the ingredients, then cooked in the kitchen and ate together outside on a big table.   

This video was spontaneous.  I had no idea what would unfold when I knocked on their door.  Maybe it was going to be an awkward day with little conversation?  Maybe the food wouldn't be tasty?  ... But turns out that it was one of the most memorable experiences in recent memory, and I hope you enjoy this special taste of Syrian food and hospitality!

Is it obvious to you yet that I am loving this country?!

tUXdYSkHrhk.title: 70 YEARS Making Mosaics (2 Syrian Brothers)
tUXdYSkHrhk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I have just discovered the most adorable, humble and friendly brothers -- Antonio and Ibrahim -- who own a mosaic shop on the side streets of Damascus, Syria!

My friend Ghaidaa and I randomly walked inside and were so impressed by their artwork and hospitality, that it was only natural to make a video on their story!

They've been working right here, in this exact shop, for the last 70 years without taking any time off -- even during the height of the war a few years ago.  It's beyond my imagination how much dedication and resistance these men have, and they do it all with a sense of humor.

Antonio and Ibrahim are a perfect example of the kindness of Syrian people -- nearly everyone I've met so far on the streets have welcomed me in the same ways that they have.

Can you see why I'm loving Syria so much?!

clUne5DtBsA.title: The World's OLDEST CITY (Damascus)
clUne5DtBsA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Syria's capital of Damascus is widely considered as the oldest continuously inhabited city on earth, with evidence of habitation dating back (at least) 11,000 years.  For all you math wizards out there, that's about 10,000 B.C.!

This is largely due to the unique positioning of the city -- in the heart of the Middle East, in the center of the world and at the intersection of 3 continents.  Damascus was conquered by Alexander the Great in 333 BCE, and since then, it's been taken over by dozens of empires such as Roman, Arab and Ottoman.

I have spent the first few days of my trip in Syria in this amazing city, and I'm loving it so much that I wanted to dedicate an entire video to show you what it's like to visit.  

One thing that I didn't mention much in the video is about how SAFE it is in Damascus.  I can't speak yet for the rest of Syria, but as far as this city goes (in this current day), I feel extremely safe just like I do in any other big city around the world.  

MORE TO COME SOON!

localized.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Syria's capital of Damascus is widely considered as the oldest continuously inhabited city on earth, with evidence of habitation dating back (at least) 11,000 years.  For all you math wizards out there, that's about 10,000 B.C.!

This is largely due to the unique positioning of the city -- in the heart of the Middle East, in the center of the world and at the intersection of 3 continents.  Damascus was conquered by Alexander the Great in 333 BCE, and since then, it's been taken over by dozens of empires such as Roman, Arab and Ottoman.

I have spent the first few days of my trip in Syria in this amazing city, and I'm loving it so much that I wanted to dedicate an entire video to show you what it's like to visit.  

One thing that I didn't mention much in the video is about how SAFE it is in Damascus.  I can't speak yet for the rest of Syria, but as far as this city goes (in this current day), I feel extremely safe just like I do in any other big city around the world.  

MORE TO COME SOON!

GhEev2Q3rFg.title: Why He Turned MUSLIM (Sal Lavallo)
GhEev2Q3rFg.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► Sal's Channel: https://bit.ly/2POG0lG
► INSTAGRAM?  https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

It's my pleasure to tell you the story of my friend, Sal Lavallo, who I actually met for the very first time yesterday in Dakar, Senegal (we've been Instagram Friends since 2014!)  

At 27 years old, Sal was the youngest person to visit every single country in the world when he completed this goal in 2017.   Thus, he's always been someone I looked up to in the travel space.

But this video is not only about his epic travels around the world -- it explains how he has transformed into a more complete, spiritual and well-rounded person primarily through converting to Islam back in 2013.

Just curious, has anyone else out there converted to Islam?  Or any other religion for that matter? I would love to hear your thoughts!

69IUIcJ8R-A.title: What is The Gambia?
69IUIcJ8R-A.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I have made it safely to Africa's smallest country on the mainland!  It's called THE GAMBIA -- have you ever heard of it before? 

This nation is completely surrounded by Senegal and the Atlantic Ocean on all sides, and it's appropriately nicknamed "The Smiling Coast of Africa."  Seriously, people smile at you from every angle here!

We've spent the past 2.5 days here and it's been a very interesting experience to say the least.  I love the people and the nature -- they are both world class.  But something doesn't feel right to me about the society, which I explain in this video.  

This West Africa road trip is getting crazier and crazier by the day!  Follow along on IG Stories for live updates in real time!

d5N8BINhcC8.title: The Art of Head-Carrying WOMEN (Guinea-Bissau)
d5N8BINhcC8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

No matter where you go on the African continent, you can see women carrying heavy loads of goods on the top of their heads and it's fascinating!   Many of them can carry up to 70% of their body weight, which is nearly impossible to do with just your two hands. 

I'm here in Guinea-Bissau, the tiny Portuguese-speaking West African nation, and I wanted to dedicate this video entirely to these strong women who have an impressive sense of balance.  

I tried to walk 5 steps with 30 kilos of rice on my head, and it's a LOT harder than I thought...

VwK-Kf6p4LY.title: Our Troubles in GUINEA (Conakry)
VwK-Kf6p4LY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

After a rough few days in Sierra Leone, we have made it onwards to the next West African country of Guinea (Conakry).

It's been a wild 2.5 days here so far, from the challenging roads to the (once again) disgusting corruption and bribery that we had to deal with.  But we made it, after 11 LONG hours of driving 150 miles, to the capital of Conakry.

Initially, we had a great time exploring the fish market at sunrise and then getting secret access inside the 2nd biggest mosque in sub Saharan Africa -- but then things quickly turned bad when thousands of policemen (armed with AK47s, helmets and bullet proof vests) stormed the streets in preparation for the riots which have been destroying the city.   

We quickly ran (literally) back to our hotel and called it a day.  We didn't leave the hotel anytime afterwards.  

This region of the world is tough to travel across, especially in your own vehicle.  At each of the dozens and dozens of police checkpoints, we are always pulled over to show our car papers/insurance, and even after we do correctly, the corrupt police will find ANY reason to pick on us (often times, making up some random law) until we pay them off.  It makes me sad. 

BUT I HAVE SOME GOOD NEWS (in case you missed yesterday's video)!  THE SIERRA LEONE GOVERNMENT SAW MY VIDEO ABOUT US GETTING SCAMMED AND THEY WENT TO THE BORDER TO ARREST THE 3 GUYS AND NOW THEY ARE IN PRISON!  One step closer to making this region a safer place to visit for everyone.

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG Stories to join my Africa trip in real time! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

O4q0sZDhxZc.title: America in Africa? (Welcome to LIBERIA)
O4q0sZDhxZc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

I have made it to the West African nation of Liberia (country 178) and I am shocked to see how much it reminds me of home!!!   Everything from the country flag, to the government system, sports culture, school curriculum and even the yellow school buses are shockingly similar to the United States, and you will find out why in this video! 

Join me today on a tour around Monrovia, the lovely capital of Liberia!

Just out of curiosity - how many of you guys out there knew that Liberia was this Americanized?  Would love to hear your thoughts.

QLgE1uQiwzs.title: What is VOODOO? (West African Religion)
QLgE1uQiwzs.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Bonjour BENIN, country #176 and I'm very excited to be here!  

When I was in Togo last year, I learned all about the religion of Voodoo -- the oldest religion in Africa.   I found it fascinating,

As soon as I got to Benin, I found out that the city of Ouidah is the center and birthplace of the religion, so I jumped in a car and took a 2 hour drive here to investigate and see what it's all about!

The best part about today was visiting the PYTHON TEMPLE, which is filled with hundreds of pythons! They are considered sacred around here.  Very interesting stuff!

nGLOaS_XTuY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Everyone say hello to the DREAM CATCHERS -- an incredible group of 9 school children living in the outskirts of Lagos, Nigeria.  

By daytime, they are learning in the classroom and by evening, they are practicing exquisite dance moves on the streets,  which has gotten the attention of Beyonce, Rihanna, P Diddy, Cardi B and right after I shot this video, ELLEN DEGENERES!! 

I had been following the Dream Catchers for months leading up to my trip to Nigeria, and I am so excited that I was able to meet them and share their inspiring story, which will make everyone around the world smile :)

YrRLCoKmLLA.title: What Can $10 Get in LAGOS, NIGERIA? (craziest city)
YrRLCoKmLLA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► Tayo's Channel: https://bit.ly/2JFeJjh   
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

HELLO FROM LAGOS, NIGERIA -- COUNTRY #175!! 🇳🇬 I truly had a lot of fun making this video inside Africa's craziest and most populated city.  Did you know that over 20 million people are living in Lagos?!   It is hands down one of the most hectic, chaotic and vibrant places I've ever been with a LOT of stories to tell. I'm overwhelmed.

My local friend and YouTuber named Tayo (his channel linked below) has been taking me all around his bustling city and we've had an absolute blast together.  Surprisingly, this was one of the hardest videos I've ever made because it's REALLY challenging to shoot content on these streets.  People don't like being on the camera here and they make a huge commotion in the streets and ask for money (etc) whenever they see it from a distance.

In any regard, I hope you enjoy this episode of my $10 series and get a glimpse into local Nigerian culture.  More to come tomorrow!

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG Stories for live updates from my Africa trip in real time: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

People don't like being on the camera here and they make a huge commotion in the streets and ask for money (etc) whenever they see it from a distance.

In any regard, I hope you enjoy this episode of my $10 series and get a glimpse into local Nigerian culture.  More to come tomorrow!

IAH7UyI4mHM.title: INSIDE SOUTH SUDAN (World's Newest Country)
IAH7UyI4mHM.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM! https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

In 2011, Sudan broke into 2 separate countries.  Sudan in the north and South Sudan in the South...  They are completely different in every way possible.

I have spent the last 48 hours in Juba, the capital city of South Sudan, and it has been one of the most interesting and eye opening trips of my entire life. 

Thankfully, was able to get in touch with some awesome locals through social media and they've been showing me around and making sure I'm safe.  I say this because South Sudan is not the safest country around Africa -- it's been in a constant state of war since its existence 8 years ago.  But things now seem to be much more stable than the past, and the future is bright for this oil rich country in Central/East Africa. 

In this video, join me as I give you a deeper look at the people, culture and life of South Sudan. Have any questions about visiting? Comment below!

3BQCxcDNC2Q.title: SUDAN is NOT What I Expected...
3BQCxcDNC2Q.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

NEWS FLASH: Everything you've heard about Sudan from the media is not the reality that exists within the borders of this peaceful North African nation.    At least, not anymore. 

Yes, they've had rough times in the past -- just like dozens of other countries in the region and around the world.  But Sudan has moved on to be a VERY SAFE COUNTRY, with some of the friendliest people I've ever met.   

Truthfully, I am a little bit shocked by how great of an experience I've had over the last 5 days in Sudan.  I did not expect things to be this smooth and amazing, but they were, and now I'm spreading the message so you can understand the truth about this country.

J0Lf1ofmaOo.title: The Forgotten PYRAMIDS OF SUDAN (better than Egypt)
J0Lf1ofmaOo.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

WOWOW - TODAY WAS A TOP 10 TRAVEL DAY OF MY ENTIRE LIFE. 

I made it to SUDAN, country #173 and one that I've long desired to visit for many reasons, but none more than to see the ancient (forgotten) pyramids.  There are more pyramids (200+) in this tiny section of Sudan than in all of Egypt, and they are just as old and impressive!

My Sudanese friends and I took a camel ride to explore around the area and we were the only ones around.  Not another soul in sight.  

If you ask me, this experience was about 10X more enjoyable than the Pyramids of Giza in Egypt, which is now flooded by tour bus after bus.   Add this place to your list!

svezgqe5fOA.title: What is ERITREA? 🇪🇷(ITALY in Africa?)
svezgqe5fOA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

HELLO FROM COUNTRY #172 - ERITREA!

I'm thrilled to be back in Africa where I will be spending the remaining 3 months of the year! Many of you probably haven’t heard of Eritrea before and that’s because it’s a relatively new country and it’s notoriously difficult to enter (top 5 in the world).  After 48 hours of roaming around the capital of Asmara and the ancient port city of Massawa, I’ve really enjoyed my time here. 

I’m getting flashbacks to when I was in Ethiopia, yet also touches of Yemen Somaliland and Italy. Yes - ITALY! Eritrea is a former Italian colony and their influence is remarkably well-preserved in the form of giant cathedrals, pizza parlors, gelato shops, old Italian cars, appertivos and many people can still speak fluent Italiano. 

The capital of Asmara is VERY safe, with kind hearted people and surprisingly the weather is cold here (2,400 meters high). Unfortunately due to WiFi issues, I haven't been able to upload anything until now, but there’s no hurry, because life is wonderful here! More to come soon 🇪🇷

38AMbRjHnjg.title: HE LOVES THE PHILIPPINES (from Syria)
38AMbRjHnjg.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Today I caught up with Basel (AKA The Hungry Syrian Wanderer) and heard his touching life story. 

In 2013, when he was a teenager, he was forced to leave his home in Syria due to war.  His neighborhood was completely destroyed from bombings.  His parents pushed him to move to the Philippines to start a new life, and although it was difficult at first to immerse into Filipino culture, he has become a successful vlogger and entrepreneur and has a very bright future ahead. 

This is a story of courage.  A story of determination.  A story of bravery.  

Hands down to Basel for all that he's done, despite not seeing his family in the last 7 years.

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram for daily travel stories: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

mmk4VMQwjGY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

While I constantly try to find the positives in every place I visit, there are few places that I just simply didn't enjoy.

hv1N7OkpAtA.title: THE $10 CHALLENGE (recap from 23 countries)
hv1N7OkpAtA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Over the last 2.5 years, I've made 23 episodes of my $10 series in 23 different countries, spending a total of $230 on 161 items. 

I made episodes in the world's most expensive countries (Norway, Hong Kong) as well as some of the cheapest (Afghanistan, Pakistan) and I've learned a lot about how far $10 can take you around the world!

This has been my favorite "series" that I have ever done, and I plan to continue making episodes until I step foot in my final country in June 2020.  This video is a recap of what I've learned so far from these $10 challenges.

I'd love to get your feedback -- do you enjoy this kind of content, or other?  Your thoughts/comments/suggestions are very important to me, as I'm constantly looking to improve my content. 

THANK YOU!

Today I got the awesome opportunity to sit down with May Chow, who  was named Asia's Best Female Chef in 2017, at her lovely restaurant in Hong Kong called Little Bao.

PBr6aN9aqyo.title: What's Happening in Hong Kong? (2019 Protests)
PBr6aN9aqyo.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

WHY IS HONG KONG IN FLAMES RIGHT NOW?

I've read a lot on the news about the recent protests in Hong Kong, so yesterday, I traveled there just to see first-hand what it's all about.  I interviewed several locals and expats to get their perspectives on these massive demonstrations that have been lasting over 3 months.

This video is not political.  I am not choosing sides or pointing fingers.  I am simply explaining what I saw with my very own eyes.

Truth be told -- it's my 7th visit to Hong Kong, one of my favorite cities in the world, and things do NOT feel normal right now.  The streets, the airport and the metro are less than half as crowded as they usually are.   Hotels are vacant.  Tourists are not around.  Shops are closing early.  It's really strange to see, and I really hope that things clear up soon so the city can go back to its thriving days.

What are your thoughts on the Hong Kong protests?  I'll be up all night reading your comments below. 

Follow @DrewBinsky on IG stories for more footage from Hong Kong: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Thank you to Antony Dapiran for the extra footage.  You can follow his Twitter @antd to stay updated on the protests.

G6jW0zj8x_M.title: WORLD'S SHORTEST MAN (26 years old, 23 inches tall)
G6jW0zj8x_M.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

This is the world's shortest man!

Today in the Philippines, I met a guy named Junrey Balawing.  

At 23.62 inches tall, he is the world's shortest man, verified by Guinness World Records in 2011.  

While your first intention might be to feel bad for him, that's not what Junrey or his father wants you to think.  The 26 year old can do many things by himself, and doctors say that he's able to live a long, normal and healthy life.  

Junrey doesn't have social media, so please comment any of your wishes below and I will pass it over to him!

8JiHuxW_RrE.title: SHE CAN'T ESCAPE YEMEN
8JiHuxW_RrE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

This is the story of a young girl named Fatima, who was born and raised in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, but was forced to move to Yemen 6 years ago.   

While most civilians in Yemen are doing everything they can to flee this horrific situation, she has done the opposite.  She went from living in a modern and peaceful country to an impoverished and dangerous one, and it's been very difficult for her to adapt.  

Can you imagine being trapped in Yemen after growing up in an advanced society in Riyadh? As much as she wants to leave to study, she must wait until the situation clears up and the borders/airports reopen.  

This video also explains her perspective on what needs to be done for Yemen to overcome this disaster and go back to how life used to be 10 years ago.  It's a fascinating interview and I enjoyed hearing her thoughts.  I hope you do too.

Dy71bb3_fzk.title: The Otherside of Yemen (I love this country!)
Dy71bb3_fzk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

I ask myself, why should I focus on the negatives when there's so many positive things to say about Yemen?

Look, there's no doubting that Yemen is undergoing some major problems like civil war, intense famine and excruciating poverty.   But when I take a second to look past that, this is truly an amazing country from the food to the historical sites and hospitality.  Yemen is capturing my heart like few countries ever have.

Please enjoy this video which shows off the good side of Yemen from my experiences in the country so far.  I really wish the media would have more stories like this in Yemen (and other countries like Afghanistan, Iran, Pakistan and Iraq) -- don't you?!
