OTfRdi4mOhw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Today I was invited into a random house for a home cooked Yemeni meal, and I decided to spontaneous film the entire experience (which was incredible)!

I can't wait for you guys to see how amazing the food and hospitality is of Yemen - it sure has caught me by surprise and I am loving it here.   

It's really important for you to see the good side of Yemen, because unfortunately, the country has suffered a lot since 2011 and has received only negative attention in the media. 

And yes, I really did eat goat brains because it's considered a delicacy here.  It tasted like cheese.

4ir-A7E5fYA.title: The MANHATTAN of YEMEN (SHIBAM)
4ir-A7E5fYA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

THIS IS FASCINATING!

Before I came to Yemen, I had NO IDEA that I would be seeing the most incredible desert landscapes of canyons and valleys, along with the most unique indigenous cultures who live inside them!  

Welcome to Wadi Dawan in the Hadramaut Governorate (region) of Yemen.  This place is made up of 32 small villages, entirely made from mud bricks!  Some of the settlements, like Shibam, are over 600 years old which has awarded them to be a UNESCO World Heritage Site.   Shibam is actually considered as the "world's first skyscraper city" and best example of urban planning based on vertical construction.

I felt 100% safe as I wandered around these villages, meeting people and seeing their humble way of living.  I was lucky enough to randomly join a wedding celebration as well!

I bet this isn't what you thought Yemen was like.  For me at least, it sure wasn't.  And this is absolutely amazing!

xYFcd61aRaw.title: Being Female in Yemen
xYFcd61aRaw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

I was lucky enough to get connected with Shrooq through an Instagram friend, and she's welcomed me into her city of Mukalla with nothing but open arms.  It's been fascinating to hear about life in Yemen from her perspective as a female, which actually has its benefits during the current situation.  

Shrooq is a young entrepreneur who is fighting for equal rights between men and women.  She's rebellious in the sense of showing her face in public, because 99% of females in her culture cover themselves from head to toe.  

Her and her friends started an activist club which revives local culture in their city for the youth, and it's amazing to see the impacts they're having on society, despite the rough times that they've been through.

In today's video, join me as I take you inside the captivating life of Shrooq.  Share this if you feel inspired!

TC5ZCACc5sg.title: I MADE IT TO YEMEN (first impressions)
TC5ZCACc5sg.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? http://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Hello to all my friends, family and followers -- I have arrived safely in Yemen and I will be exploring deep into the country by myself and one local guy over the next week.

Yemen is (by far) the most difficult country in the world to visit in terms of logistics (getting a visa, planning, etc) and staying safe.  I'm sure you are aware that since 2011, Yemen has been in a constant state of war.  Tourists are not welcome here, and it's extremely risky for any traveler to visit at this moment -- especially as both an American and a journalist. I am double at risk.

That all being said, I am beyond excited to have this rare opportunity to take you inside one of the most hidden and raw cultures left on earth.  My first 24 hours has already been one hell of an emotional ride (as you'll see in this video) -- and you will be hearing lots more over the coming week. 

You won't want to miss this series, trust me!

If you're on Instagram, join me on IG Stories for more updates: https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

RYsEetvUXTY.title: The RAREST HORSE on Earth (Akhal-Teke)
RYsEetvUXTY.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Any horse lovers out there?!

In Turkmenistan, horses are so loved that they are considered a family member.  They have a specific breed of horse, called the Akhal-Teke, which is only found here and it's one of the most unique animals I've ever seen!

They are known for their speed, intelligence, endurance and ability to withstand extreme temperatures as they live in the desert.  There are currently less than 6,000 Akhal-Teke horses left on earth, and I was lucky enough to visit 70 of them today in a small farm outside of Ashgabat, Turkmenistan.

More to come tomorrow from this fascinating country!

Stay updated with my trip on IG Stories! https://instagram.com/drewbinsky

hmIa2SGpm6s.title: World's Strangest City (ASHGABAT, TURKMENISTAN)
hmIa2SGpm6s.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

Have you ever heard of TURKMENISTAN before?  If not, then get ready to learn about how strange it is here in my 170th country. 

I've spent the last 24 hours roaming around the capital city of Ashgabat, and IT REMINDS ME EXACTLY OF PYONGYANG, NORTH KOREA in just about every way possible.  Huge fancy buildings with very few people inside perfectly manicured gardens and boulevards with nobody on them and this eerie feeling that someone is watching over my shoulder 24/7. TURKMENISTAN IS WEIRD. 

People had told me that Ashgabat was strange, but I had no idea to what extent it was until arriving here.... Find out everything you need to know about Turkmenistan's capital in this video!

How many of you guys actually knew about this place? Would love to see a show of hands :)

TNktJQKRzns.title: 11 Billion Tons of Ice Melted (TODAY IN GREENLAND)
TNktJQKRzns.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

IT'S REALLY HOT IN GREENLAND RIGHT NOW... Like 15 degrees Celsius or 60 Fahrenheit. THIS IS NOT NORMAL.

Today alone, Greenland's ice sheet (the second largest on earth) lost a record 11 billion tons, which rose global ocean levels half a millimeter.   

It was bizarre to witness this first hand, as our Hurtigruten expedition explored the sea ice on small tender boats.  

No region on earth is more affected more by climate change than the polar regions, and you don't realize how big the issue is until you see it with your own eyes.  I made this video to raise awareness because it's up to us to fix it.  I am speechless by what I saw today.

Please share your thoughts, comments and suggestions on climate change.  I want to get some discussion going about what is happening right now on our lovely planet.

xy3UzXvqhgI.title: He Lives with Polar Bears
xy3UzXvqhgI.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Meet Niels - he is from one of the world's most isolated towns (Ittoqqortoormiit, Greenland).  He grew up alongside polar bears and massive glaciers inside the largest national park and fjord system on earth.   He knows all 350 residents in his town by name and the closest city is thousands of kilometers away.

Despite traveling and studying overseas, he chooses to remain back home because he loves his hometown.  That's very admirable!

It was a pleasure spending the day with Niels in one of the most fascinating places I've ever been.  I hope to go back again another in the wintertime!

nCO4TBjml5A.title: The World's GREENEST SHIP! (Battery Powered)
nCO4TBjml5A.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

HELLO FROM THE ARCTIC!  We've already seen 3 polar bears in their natural habitat!

Do you guys remember how much fun we had in Antarctica with Hurtigruten a few years ago?  We're back for round 2, but this time we are exploring some of the most remote areas on earth in North Eastern Greenland, followed by the wonders of Iceland. 

The innovative ship that we are currently on is called the MS Amundsen and it was completed just a few weeks ago. It's the world's first battery powered hybrid expedition cruise ship -- think of a Toyota Prius on the sea!  It's extremely impressive, and Hurtigruten is revolutionizing how we explore our oceans in the most sustainable way possible.

I can't wait to show you more of Eastern Greenland over the next few days!

NE40-xC107E.title: Is This Place Real? (Barentsburg)
NE40-xC107E.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► TEXT ME!  +1 310 349 3854

Did you know that there is an abandoned Russian settlement in the Arctic called Barentsburg?  Wait until you see this!!

Today was a wild adventure, to say the least.  

I took a 2 hour boat ride from Longyearbyen (the biggest town in Svalbard) which is under Norwegian control, over to Barentsburg (the second-biggest town in Svalbard) which is under Russian control.

The two towns could not be any more different. 

After visiting 169 countries and more than 500 cities, I find Barentsburg to be the absolute most bizarre town in the world.   

It was purchased by the Soviet Union about 90 years ago from the Dutch because of the on-site coal mine... While there are about 400 Russian & Ukrainian miners still working here today, it's a failing business, and it's obvious that Russia keeps this place alive because they want a presence in the Arctic (think natural resources, trade routes, etc).  

Walking around Barentsburg gave me flash backs to North Korea.  Abandoned buildings.  Seemingly staged people and culture.   I still can't quite wrap my head around this!

If you enjoyed this video, please share it!  It's one of my top 10 favorites I think.  

TEXT ME +1 310 349 3854 and I will respond :)

VF8dkjEdKNo.title: HE IS THE ICE MAN (Wim Hof)
VF8dkjEdKNo.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

EVERYONE, MEET WIM HOF!

Yesterday, I flew from Madrid to Amsterdam and back to Madrid in the same day, just to spend a few hours with The Iceman (Wim Hof) in his countryside home. 

I did my first ever ice bath, and words cannot express how powerful this experience has been!

Wim Hof has spent his entire life defying reality by immersing himself in freezing temperatures, solely for the ability to control his mind to live a stress free life. 

He developed the "Wim Hof Method," which is practiced by millions of people around the world. It uses a combination of breathing, meditation and gradual cold exposure to train your brain to get rid of any mental disorders such as anxiety, depression and fear. 

The Ice Man has 26 Guinness World records, for mind-blowing things such as running marathons, barefoot, in the snow, staying in constant contact with ice for almost 2 hours, and hiking 7,200 meters high on Mt. Everest without pants on.

This guy is one of the most inspiring human beings on the planet, and it has been an honor to meet him. 

Wim wants his voice to be spread as far and wide as possible, so if you find his message inspiring, then please share this video with your friends! To join one of Wim's free miniclasses, check this link: https://www.wimhofmethod.com/free-mini-class.

Are you on Instagram? Join me @DrewBinsky for more stories from every single country: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

ou97kdQXkEQ.title: She's Getting a Degree Around the World
ou97kdQXkEQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

This is the story of a young Spanish girl named Kenya, who is taking a much different approach to getting her college degree.   

Instead of staying on one campus, attending boring lecture halls and taking final exams -- her innovative schooling system, called Minerva, is 100% online and involves debating and learning REAL WORLD tactics.  There are 130 people in her class who come from 65 countries and they are constantly traveling, living in 7 different countries for 4 months at a time.  

I'd love to get your thoughts on whether you think this is the future of education or not?  I certainly think it is a lot more valuable than the "traditional colleges" that we know of today.

Are you on Instagram? Join me @DrewBinsky!

T0yNDtDBxvM.title: What is a SIESTA? (Spanish Culture)
T0yNDtDBxvM.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

I've really been enjoying my time in Madrid over the last week -- it's my first time here!!  While there are many things I admire about Spanish culture, nothing stands out more than the SIESTA CULTURE (or short power naps after lunch).

Have you ever heard of a siesta before?

All of the stereotypes are true (especially in the summer months) -- people really do take siestas here and it's magnificent!  Why can't we have a siesta culture in the U.S. as well?  It makes a lot of sense!

Comment below if you love taking siestas like they do in Spain!  

Follow @DrewBinsky on Instagram Stories for BTS of my travels :)

yn74bA_IhIQ.title: He's Going Back to 9-5
yn74bA_IhIQ.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

This is my friend Alvaro.  He is a popular Instagrammer from Spain who is also on a mission to visit every country in the world (currently he's at 177/197).  We've actually known each other for 4 years online, and this is the first time we've met in real life!

What's interesting about Alvaro is not only the fact that he's visiting every country (there are hundreds of people doing it as we speak) -- but it's that he plans to return to a 9-5 job in the corporate world.   In today's society, everyone wants to be "famous" and be an "influencer" -- and while Alvaro has that fame now, he doesn't see it being sufficient for long term.

All things considered, he is still planning to travel and post amazing photos (and you should all follow him @Wanderreds) -- and he's an awesome dude.  You will be seeing a lot more of him as we will be spending several weeks traveling West Africa together in October!

Cx1ChaRb2NE.title: How VIETNAMESE is PRAGUE?
Cx1ChaRb2NE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Vietnamese people in Prague?  

Don't get confused by this title, there is actually a massive Vietnamese community in the Czech Republic -- especially right here in Prague!

I remember when I lived in Prague 7 years ago that there was a lot of Vietnamese restaurants, but I never really dug deeper to find out why they were here.  And now, I've realized that many of them came to Czechoslovakia during the communism period to work or study, and then when communism fell in the early 90s, they never left.

Here is the full story of the Vietnamese influence of Prague, which I find to be fascinating and incredible.

Thanks for the shots Michael Makes Films.  Instagram: @DrewBinsky

N59DHWilq0c.title: She's Saving Her Culture (NIGER)
N59DHWilq0c.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

It's time to put Niger on the map!

When I arrived in Niger yesterday, my 168th country, I was picked up at the airport by an Instagram friend named Aminata.  

Little did I know that she'd be one of the coolest people I've ever met in my life!

After living in Germany for the last 7 years, she was fed up when people would mistake her for being 'Nigerian' (the English-speaking country next door).  So she recently moved back to her hometown of Niamey, Niger to start an NGO promoting her country's culture and traditions.  In a sense, she is the one and only 'cultural ambassador' for her Niger and she is doing big things like organizing the first international cultural festival in August.

In our globalized world of fast-paced, cut-throat societies -- it's imperative for us to preserve our beautiful cultures, like Aminata is doing with Niger. 

Share this video to help Aminata's goal of putting her country on the map!  I may add, an amazing country that is :)

Follow me on Instagram for more stories! @DrewBinsky.  And Aminata's Insta is @SensaiCulture

7nJKbLpBRE0.title: The Biggest Country in Africa (ALGERIA)
7nJKbLpBRE0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

ALGERIA... WHO KNEW IT'S THIS AMAZING?

I've spent the last 4 days road tripping around the Northern Mediterranean coast of ALGERIA, and I have been absolutely stunned by what I've experienced.   From the warm hearts to the stunning nature and complete mix of cultures, I can safely say that this country is one of the most underrated in the world.

And it's huge... REALLY HUGE.

After Sudan split into two countries in 2011, Algeria emerged as the largest country in Africa by size.  It's so big that only 12% of the land is inhabited (with 44 million people), and over 90% of its surface is covered in the Sahara desert.  

If the visa wasn't so hard to get, then this country would explode in tourism.  But I kind of like it the way it is -- I didn't come across a single tourist during my time here. 

Algeria is, without question, the most surprising country in Africa for me so far, and I know with certainty that I'll be back.  Insha'Allah!

Follow Drew Binsky for daily travel videos.  Instagram @DrewBinsky

WHERE IS HIS HOME? SLOVAKIA OR THAILAND?

I'd like to introduce you to my good friend, Juraj.  We met last year while living in his (current) home of Bangkok, and now I am visiting his (original) home of Myjava, Slovakia.  He has been living abroad for the last 11 years.

It's very interesting to see how Juraj's perspectives have changed so much after living overseas for so long, but when he comes back home, it's all the same as he remembers.

The same feeling happens to me every time I go home, and I'm just curious how many of you guys can relate to this situation?  Comment below, I'd love to hear from you!

THE POWER OF HARD WORK AS A VIDEO MAKER!

As I approach 2 million Facebook friends and 1 billion overall views, I'd like to recap how I got here and share with you some of my realizations from this crazy journey to every country in the world.

It hasn't been easy making daily videos and my job is quite stressful, especially when you get food poisoning or when your flight get cancelled or when you don't have strong enough wifi to upload -- but in the end, I love my job. THIS GUY IS AN EXTREME TRAVELER!

Today I had the pleasure of meeting Peter, a 26 year guy from Slovakia, who might be the most adventurous and courageous traveler out there. 

From bribing police officers in Benin to getting a severe case of malaria in Togo to being caught in a civil war in Cameroon -- Peter is not afraid of anything!

What a life, what a guy, and I hope to see him again!

N2rnBxCmbIE.title: What's a Döner Kebab? (#1 Street Food in BERLIN)
N2rnBxCmbIE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

If you've ever been to BERLIN, then you already know how popular (and freaking) tasty a DÖNER KEBAB is... It's the #1 street food of the city and you can find them almost on every corner.

But I know you might be confused, because the Turkish people invented the (original) kebab... but after WWII, loads of Turkish immigrants flocked to Berlin and here, they put a modern spin on their classic kebab and they called it a döner kebab.   In all honesty, it's one of the best things you can possibly eat! 

Share this video with your friends if you love döner kebabs!

Are you on Instagram? Come say hi on Instagram @DrewBinsky!  And special thanks to my friend Katie, who I met in Iraq 6 weeks ago, for taking us around Berlin!

lsZI58MO3kE.title: Who Are THE AMISH? (Lancaster, Pennsylvania)
lsZI58MO3kE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

WHO ARE THE AMISH PEOPLE OF AMERICA?

One thing I love about the USA is the diversity.  You can pretty much find people from all cultures, religions, traditions and walks of life inside of this country of 327 million people.

One of the most interesting groups of people that I've come across are the AMISH.   They are traditional Christian Anabaptists who originally have Swiss German roots, and settled (mostly) in Pennsylvania in the early 18th Century.

I went to Lancaster Country, PA today to learn all about their way of life, and it's fascinating!  Have you ever heard of the Amish before?

Follow me on Instagram @DrewBinsky for more travel content.  Huge thank you to Amish Farm and House for taking us around!

I went to Lancaster Country, PA today to learn all about their way of life, and it's fascinating!  Have you ever heard of the Amish before?

Follow me on Instagram @DrewBinsky for more travel content.  Huge thank you to Amish Farm and House for taking us around!

A7vcLYIxJvk.title: She Escaped North Korea to Live in South Korea
A7vcLYIxJvk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me: https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky/

WONDER WHAT IT's LIKE TO ESCAPE NORTH KOREA?

We've all heard stories about people escaping North Korea for a better life... and today in Seoul, I was able to sit down with one ambitious North Korean girl named Nara, to hear what she went through.

Long story short, Nara escaped North Korea in 2015 by swimming over a river into China. Then she illegally entered Thailand without a passport, where she was thrown in jail for 1 month.  After getting in touch with the South Korean embassy, they granted her citizenship and allowed her to move to Seoul.

While it was difficult for her to adjust to South Korean culture at first, she now lives a great life as an actress on TV and making videos for her YouTube and Instagram accounts (@kang_naraa)

This has been a special story for me to create because I spent 4 days in North Korea in 2017 and I got a glance at what society she grew up in...  We chatted about everything from her thoughts on Kim Jong-un to the struggles that she faces adjusting to life in South Korea today.

If you find Nara's story inspiring - share this video with your friends!

mee95-aUnZA.title: This Religion Survived ISIS (YAZIDIS)
mee95-aUnZA.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

A story about the Yazidis and the genocide of Yazidism by ISIS.

This is a very sad story, but one that I feel needs to be told because of the lack of international attention that the Yazidi people have received.

In short, the Yazidis -- who are both an ethnic group and religion -- were targeted and attacked by ISIS in 2014.  On August 3rd of that year, ISIS stormed in one of their beloved towns called Shingal, killing men by the thousands and forcing women into sexual slavery.   And those women who didn't follow their rules (including converting to Islam) were killed.

Today I went to the tiny mountainous village in North Eastern Iraq called Lalish -- which is the site of the holiest temple in Yazidism.  Is it their "Mecca" equivalent. In Lalish, it is forbidden to wear shoes to acknowledge the purity of their religion.  

I met some people who survived the genocide and I asked them a few questions.  This is what they have to say.

This content is not my favorite to make. It's difficult.  It's raw.  It's depressing.  But once again, I feel like it is extremely important to raise awareness -- especially in this case, as it just happened 5 years ago.

Join me on Instagram @drewbinsky.

jlw7YRXDyI4.title: He Walked Across Pakistan... TWICE
jlw7YRXDyI4.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Before I came to Pakistan, dozens of people reached out and told me that I had to find a man named Naveed Khan -- AKA the guy who walked across Pakistan TWICE.

So I found his Instagram (@hunzaonfoot), sent him a message, a lucky we happened to be in Islamabad at the same time (he's usually in the Hunza Valley mountains).   

I was amazed to hear his story. 

Join me as I tell you how Naveed got inspired to walk 5,100 kilometers across Pakistan, Afghanistan and India.  If you are ever planning to visit Northern Pakistan or the Hunza Valley, then Naveed is your guy!

And also, for all of you out there who still thinks that Pakistan is "unsafe" -- then hearing Naveed's story will prove you wrong!

Join me on Instagram @drewbinsky, and also join Naveed on Instagram (@huzaonfoot).

wSwAY12uVZI.title: What is KASHMIR? (India vs Pakistan vs China)
wSwAY12uVZI.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Guess what guys?  I am the VERY FIRST TOURIST EVER to be allowed into Azad Kashmir without a permit.  The government lifted restrictions TODAY and I am thrilled to be able to experience this untouched society. 

If you've never heard of Kashmir before, it's a disputed territory of some 13 million people that lies in the Himalayan mountains in between Northern India, Northern Pakistan and Western China.  Each of the 3 countries claims ownership in the land, which is what has caused all the recent controversy.

But all politics aside, this place is SO AMAZING and I am loving the culture out here.  Who would have known that Kashmir is this stunning?  Did you?

Fact: I came to Pakistan and I haven't spent any money.

Because nobody will let me.  Seriously.  Pakistan has the world's best hospitality, by a long shot.

SQQy11h-Pf8.title: Behind the Scenes of My Life (Daily Video Making)
SQQy11h-Pf8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Today, I'd like to take you behind the scenes of my daily life as a video creator.  

Long story short, IT'S A LOT MORE WORK THAN YOU THINK.

It takes me roughly 15 hours to make each 3-4 minute video that you see pop up on your newsfeed every day (idea creation, scripting, scouting locations, meeting locals, shooting, editing, uploading)...

I work 7 days a week, 365 days a year -- even on holidays, days when I'm flying over an ocean (like today) and when I am sick.  I guess you can call it an addition, and I am not planning to stop making daily travel videos until I step foot in my 197th country (hopefully in January 2020!).

If you are also a video maker, then you will feel me on constant struggles and pressure that we go through to deliver compelling stories.   It's not easy, and it does take a certain person who is able (and willing) to push themselves mentally and physically on a daily basis.    

And while it may seem like I am complaining -- that is not the case.  I love my job and I cannot imagine doing anything else!  I have found my niche, my voice, and my happiness with showing you all the world through my lens!

If you are reading this right now, I want to say thank you for joining me on this wild adventure.  Bigger and better things to come, I promise!  #Pakistan #Afghanistan #Iraq

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Thank you Michael Makes Films for helping me shoot this video together.

AdCZP7oJ528.title: HER NAME IS KEVIN
AdCZP7oJ528.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Today I want to introduce you to Kevin, a transgender woman from the Philippines who is a front runner in representing the LGBT community.

Despite living in a Catholic-dominated country, Kevin has gained a lot of attention for winning the most prestigious transgender beauty pageant in the world.  She is also the first transgender to represent a huge global brand that caters only towards women.

I met up with Kevin today to learn more about her inspiring story. Follow her on Instagram @KevinBalot to stay updated with her journey. Also, her Youtube is linked below:

https://m.youtube.com/thegirlnamedkevin/

QUESTION: How is the LGBT progress in your country?  Here in the Philippines, it is becoming more widely accepted, and I'm happy to see these positive changes.

Join me on Instagram @drewbinsky.    Special thanks to Michael (IG: @michaelmakesfilms) for the edits, and Deanna for inspiring me to share her story (IG: @deannasallao)!

8HxYx7uhHW0.title: The Challenge of my Last 36 Countries (MONEY, FLIGHTS, VISAS)
8HxYx7uhHW0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

MABUHAY from the Philippines!  I'm so happy to be back in my favorite country for the 32nd time -- and we've decided to make a new "home base" here for the next 6 weeks!  

I have now visited 161 countries, which means that I have 36 left to complete my lifelong goal of visiting every country in the world.  

2019 will be the year that I (hopefully) get to step foot in my 197th country, but it's going to be a loooong, tedious, and exciting journey to get there. 

This video explains some of the challenges that I will face as I plan to enter some of the most difficult and least visited countries in the world. 

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Upcoming travels: Pakistan, Norway, Afghanistan

WecOxYbOqk0.title: What is a CHINDIAN?
WecOxYbOqk0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me http://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

One of my favorite things about Malaysia is the diversity among it's people.  Walking around the streets of Kuala Lumpur, I am always stunned by the multi-cultural, multi-ethic and multi-lingual locals that I come across.

Malaysia's two biggest ethnic groups (aside from Malay) are Chinese and Indian -- and when you mix their blood together over the decades, you have this amazing sub-ethnic group called "Chindians."  

I met some Chindians today in K.L. and I wanted to give you a glimpse into their lives in this video.

If you are a Chindian, I'd love to hear your story below (struggles and/or advantages)?  Personally, I think they are a beautiful thing because Chindians can get the best of BOTH worlds (think Indian weddings and Chinese food).

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Special thanks to (IG: @MichaelMakesFilms) for the shots and The Rojak Projek for making this video happen!

iiuhavJSwuc.title: 10 Wacky Things About Thai Culture
iiuhavJSwuc.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

As I'm getting ready to leave my home of Bangkok tomorrow morning until August, I feel like it's necessary to make this video about Thai culture... which I've been thinking about creating for months!   

Before you watch this video, please know that I love Thailand with all my heart.  It's a wonderful country with incredibly warm people, the tastiest of food and a super lively culture.   Deanna and I moved here last June and we have been very happy out here in just about every way possible.

BUT... that all being said... Thailand has a unique and offbeat culture that may leave you scratching your head if you come from the U.S. (or any Western country for that matter). This video explains the 10 wackiest things I find about Thai culture.

Have you ever been to Thailand? What are your favorite tings about Thai culture?  Please share your thoughts below!

mNN8zY3N9Gw.title: He's Going to Every Country Without Flying!
mNN8zY3N9Gw.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

Thor is one of the most ambitious and courageous human beings on this planet, and I'm glad to have finally caught him in Bangkok after 4 years of being internet friends!

This Danish man left his home in October 2013 with a goal to visit every single country in one continuous journey without flying on a single airplane.  So far, he's made it to 174 countries by means of container ships, trains, buses and taxis -- and he's done it all on $20 USD per day!

Just wait until you hear the rest of his story -- it's one of my favorite yet. 

Share this video with all of your travel friends, and let's root Thor onto the finish line!

PP-e-2k_XFs.title: 8 Budget Tips to Travel ASIA for $50/day
PP-e-2k_XFs.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Asia has been my home since 2013 and I adore this continent more than any other.  

I've lived in South Korea, Vietnam, the Philippines and Thailand -- and I've traveled to roughly 90% of the countries on the continent.  Asia is my home, my happiness and my comfort zone.

One of the best parts about traveling in Asia is the affordability!  So in this video, I share some of my best travel tips if you are coming to Asia on a budget!  Yes, it really is possible to travel Asia on less than $50 per day, all in.

Do you have any other tips to add? Please comment them below!

20ei1DM2NL8.title: 6 Things I Love About the PACIFIC ISLANDS (Travel Guide)
20ei1DM2NL8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Want to visit the Pacific Islands? Watch this video!

Hi from Samoa -- I am nearing the end of my 3 week trip around the Pacific Islands, and now I have just Tonga and Palau left until I complete them all!

I absolutely love traveling in the Pacific Islands -- from the vibrant culture to the enriching nature and everything in between.   This video contains my 6 favorite things about traveling in the Pacific Islands, as well as some of my best travel tips if you are planning to come here!

Please comment any questions you have about the Pacific Islands, and I'll get back to you :)

Follow @drewbinsky on IG STORIES for behind-the-scenes of my travels.  36 COUNTRIES LEFT

J0DxNvCFI8g.title: The Most Important Thing I've Ever Told You
J0DxNvCFI8g.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Please listen to what I have to say in this video, because it's terrifying.  

I just happened to come to Tuvalu during the highest "King Tide" ever, and I could not believe my eyes.  

I am witnessing a country that is on the brink of drowning, and it should no longer go unnoticed.  

Share this video to spread the message and help put the innocent country of Tuvalu on people’s minds.   

Just like many other nations in the Pacific, the people of Tuvalu are going to need help in one way or another, and it's going to take a global effort to figure it out.

FL0U4tJ0Ezk.title: What is KAVA? (This Drink is INSANE)
FL0U4tJ0Ezk.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

If you've never heard of KAVA before, then prepare to get your mind blown by what I'm about to tell you...  

Kava is unbelievably popular across the Pacific Islands, especially right here on Pohnpei island in Micronesia.  Kava is made from the roots of the kava plant, mixed with hibiscus plant and then squeezed out into a cup.  Kava is one of the most interesting drinks I've ever seen, and I can't wait to tell you all about it in this video!

What are your thoughts on legal, 100% natural remedies such as kava?  Would you ever try it?

7Ni4gcl4tpE.title: This Country is Disappearing 😢
7Ni4gcl4tpE.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
📝 Join my Newsletter & Get a Secret Video of my Best Travel Hacks! https://bit.ly/3ebkR0Y

Climate change has never felt more real to my eyes until I arrived here in KIRIBATI - an island nation in the Central Pacific Ocean.

The rising sea levels are quickly shrinking this country, which has a peak altitude of 3 meters.  It's projected to be entirely underwater by the year 2100. 
 
While many countries are feeling the impacts of climate change, nobody is more threatened right now than the 100,000+ residents of Kiribati.

The question now becomes, how do we prevent the people here from becoming climate refugees?  The only 4 options I can think of are the following:

1. Build a higher sea wall (which will cost billions of USD)
2. Buy land overseas for them to relocate (will also cost a fortune)
3. Send more Kiribati citizens abroad (i.e. Australia and New Zealand) for jobs, and they can slowly adapt to a new life 
4. Boost tourism in Kiribati so people can see first hand the affects of climate change, which will also pump money back in to the economy

Would love to get your thoughts on what we can do to help the wonderful people of Kiribati.  I encourage you all to get creative and share your best solutions below.  I will be reading and responding to as many comments as I can, and I encourage you to do the same. This is important.

mrBhE0nqkis.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1

Have you ever seen dark skinned people with bright blonde hair?... Me either, until I arrived in my 154th country -- THE SOLOMON ISLANDS!!

I just discovered that 5-10% of Solomon Islanders have natural blonde hair, and it's the only place in the world (Melanesia) where you can see dark skinned people with natural blonde hair.  It's absolutely amazing and I can't get enough of these beautiful faces.

DkDseujXmz0.title: BANGKOK IS ON HIGH ALERT (air pollution)
DkDseujXmz0.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Deanna and I moved to Bangkok 7 months ago for many reasons, such as the affordability, central location, great networking and tasty food.  There’s a lot that I love about this city and I’ve been happy to call it my home… until this past week. 

The city has been ENGULFED in the worst toxic smog (air pollution) in its history, and it’s causing massive health concerns among the 15 million+ residents.  

The air is so contaminated that many of Bangkok’s public schools have been closed down for the past week.  A few days ago, it was so smoggy that I could not see 10 meters in front of me.   

This is not a joke and it needs to be taken seriously.  We (humans) created this problem, and now it’s up to us to prevent it from happening again.

ZDUUdMPYx-8.title: He's THE KING of Smoked Meat
ZDUUdMPYx-8.description:
► SUBSCRIBE for daily travel videos: http://bit.ly/2hyQnZ1
► INSTAGRAM? Join me @drewbinsky!

Does anyone like MEAT? Let me introduce you to the king of smoked meat!

We are on a weekend getaway 2.5 hours north of Bangkok to a lovely National Park called Khao Yai...  This pristine nature and fresh air feels like a different world from polluted Bangkok, and it's been a great trip so far.

Earlier today, I was introduced to a man named Book (AKA Ribs mannn) who is literally the KING of smoked meat.  Everybody knows him, not only here in his hometown, but all over Thailand.  

People flock from around the country to wait in long queues to try his famous smoked pork, beef and chicken at his state-of-the-art restaurant that you need to see with your own eyes to believe.

If you ever come to Thailand, don't miss out on this experience!

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Thanks Michael (IG @affinityadventure) for the edits!

uoqsYWfqSIE.title: He Traveled 15,000 KM Solo by Land
uoqsYWfqSIE.description:
Today I had the pleasure of meeting an amazing 23 year old traveler from Thailand named Petch, who just finished a solo trip going overland from Bangkok to Morocco -- that's 15,000+ kilometers over 115 days and 29 countries.  

Wow.

He's aiming to be the first Thai-born person to visit every country in the world, and he's well on his way to achieve his goal!

Would you have the guts to go on a trip like that?  I'm not sure I do... too lonely and too long without wifi 😅

Join Petch's travels on IG (@sidepackstory).  

Follow @drewbinsky on Instagram for more stories!  Thanks for the edits, Michael @affinityadventure!

VwO8SOn_cWQ.title: From Broke to Millionaires at 22 (DIGITAL NOMADS)
VwO8SOn_cWQ.description:
I met Mac and Jess a week ago in Bangkok, and I couldn't believe my ears when they told me their story of going from $50,000 in debt to generating $1.5 million by working online.

So I decided to share their journey with you as an inspiration that there ARE so many opportunities are out there to be successful and you CAN follow your dream life, whatever it may be. 

As millennials, sometimes it's hard for us to convince our parents (trust me) that we can make a sustainable living online.  The internet simply wasn't around when they grew up. 

But it's 2019 now, and times have changed.   A recent study by CNBC found out that 70% of people globally work remotely at least once a week and 53% work remotely for at least half of the week.  

I just get so happy when I cross paths with people like Mac and Jess, who are taking advantage of the opportunities around them, and crushing it!

Share this video if you feel inspired :)

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Thanks Michael (IG @affinityadventure) for the help making this video!

cIRnYKgq0RA.title: How Much $$$ to Visit EVERY COUNTRY IN THE WORLD?
cIRnYKgq0RA.description:
One of the most common questions I get is about BUDGETING... "How expensive is it to travel to every country in the world?"

This is not an easy question to answer, because there are so many factors to consider... but as I have just 40 countries remaining, I thought I'd do my best to share the estimated cost to complete my lifelong goal of visiting every single country.

That cost is about $700 per country, multiplied by 193 is $135,000 total.  For context, that's the price of a new Audi R8.  

 Join me on Instagram @drewbinsky :D

X0UVm3lH93A.title: North vs. South INDIA... Two Different Worlds
X0UVm3lH93A.description:
TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

On my last trip to India, I visited only the North and that's what I thought all of India was like.  

This trip, I did only the South and it's completely opposite from the North in every way imaginable!

The best way to think about India is like Europe.  When you move from one Indian state to the next -- the culture, cuisine, language and weather all change in the same way that you'd experience by hopping European countries. 

Have you ever been to India?  What do you think are the biggest differences between the North and the South?  Please share your thoughts below!

oKiwnbX_omM.title: Muslims vs. Jews... Are We The Same?
oKiwnbX_omM.description:
https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Muslims and Jews... Islam and Judaism.  What do you think when you hear these words together in the same sentence?  If you're like most people, you will think hatred and negativity...  But from my experiences traveling in Muslim-majority countries and openly telling everyone I am Jewish, I've had the opposite experiences.

I love Muslims.  They are amazing souls.  I've made many great Muslim friends over the years and I will continue to do so.  Growing up Jewish, I've realized that Muslims and Jews have SO MANY of the same traditions and values.  

I've been wanting to make this video for a while as the message is strong.  Please watch to the end, and share it with your friends if you agree that Muslims and Jews are the same.

Follow @drewbinsky on instagram for daily travel stories.

Cbbke6EsYb4.title: Traveling to 50 Countries... with 2 Kids!
Cbbke6EsYb4.description:
Hi Guys! I have a really exciting video to share with you today.  Meet the traveling Goy's (AKA the Wonderlusters) -- I bumped into them this morning at a temple in Sri Lanka, and after speaking with them for a bit, I decided to make this spontaneous video of their inspiring journey. 

Long story short, this family of 4 sold everything back home (Quebec, Canada) to go on a 15 MONTH trip to 50 COUNTRIES for LESS THAN $70,000 USD TOTAL. 

I caught them half way on their journey, and I was very impressed to hear about their adventures. I know how tedious it is to plan long trips (as a solo traveler), and I could not imagine doing it for 4 people... not to mention, the patience they have to constantly watch over a 9 and 7 year old!

The Goy's use all sorts of travel hacks to minimize their expenses (i.e. 16 credit cards to collect points) and they homeschool their youngsters on the road.   If you ask me, no kids on this planet are getting a better education right now than Mateo and Luka, as they experience first-hand the wonders of the world.

Share this video if you feel inspired (and if you wish your parents would have taken you to 50 countries before you turned 10)!

Follow @drewbinsky on Insta for daily travel stories.  You can follow the Goy's journey on Facebook @The Wonderlusters around the world and on Instagram @wonderlustrs.

frU_BvAp0DU.title: The Biggest Fish in India? (Chennai Fish Market)
frU_BvAp0DU.description:
My alarm rang at 3:30AM this morning to see some fish at the Chennai Fish Market.  I jumped in a taxi and headed to the Chennai Fish Market — one of the biggest fish markets in India — to catch the wholesale auction…. and the fish were HUGE!

Over the years, I've enjoyed going to fish markets across Asia, from South Korea to Hong Kong to Japan…  but I've never seen chaos like I've seen this morning in Chennai.  

It's crowded.  It's grimy.  It's loud.  But it's all part of the experience, and I'm excited to share it with you in this video!

Would you ever go to an early morning fish market?  I highly recommend it for a different travel experience!

Follow @drewbinsky on Instagram for more content from India!  Huge shoutout to Michael (IG @affinityadventure) for shooting and editing this entire video.  Lots of hours were poured into this one

6w3fWu7lqJo.title: The Real Life Burning Man... (Auroville)
6w3fWu7lqJo.description:
The biggest reason I came to India was to visit Auroville and make this video so you all can learn about this bizarre experimental community.  It's like burning man on steroids.

I seriously cannot believe what I just experienced.  A town of complete unity and togetherness, with 3,000+ residents who come from 57 countries around the world.   A cashless society that has no religion, no laws and a 0% crime rate.   A place where anything is possible, and encouraged, with the most laidback lifestyle I've ever seen. 

This is the real life Burning Man... and it's been around since 1968!

Have you ever heard about Auroville? What are your thoughts about it?

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Thank you Michael (IG @affinityadventure) for the shots & edits.  

PS - This video probably won't get the most views, but I had the most fun shooting it and putting this story together.  I love telling unique stories, such as Auroville, which are happening around our world.  If you have thoughts or comments on Auroville, please share below! I will be reading them all :)

4F3CG95HGCo.title: Top 3 South Indian Foods!
4F3CG95HGCo.description:
Have you ever tried SOUTH Indian food?!  It's completely different than the North, and in humble opinion, it's much tastier!

An overwhelming majority of Indian restaurants abroad (seriously, like 99% of them) are serve North Indian food...  But there's a whole new world of flavors, spices and ingredients down in South India, so please allow me and my local friend, Azhar, to introduce you to our favorite dishes in the Kerala (SOUTH INDIAN FOOD!!)

Have you ever tried South Indian food? What's your favorite dish?  Mine is DOSA all the way!

And join me on Instagram @drewbinsky :D   Thanks Michael for the shots & edits, and thanks again to Azhar for being the best guide ever.  More coming soon!

jEGrZ37E39g.title: Married at First Sight?
jEGrZ37E39g.description:
The way people fall in love in India is not common in the Western World.    It's marriage at first sight!

Most weddings in India are 'arranged marriages,' where a marriage broker matches you with someone who meets your qualifications and social status (age, religion, etc).  In a sense, marriage brokers in India function the same way as Tinder does in the West.

Then, the person seeking love proceeds to go on several dates (5-10 minutes) until they find 'the one.'   Once both parties agree that they want to spend the rest of their lives together, they decide to get married on the spot.   The next time they meet is usually on their wedding day, where hundreds (or thousands) of friends and family members celebrate.

If anyone reading this had an arranged marriage, please share your story below because it'll be interesting to hear more success stories!

Follow Drew Binsky for daily travel videos.  Instagram @drewbinsky.   

Thanks to my buddy Anto for letting me share your personal story of how you met your wife!  And thanks to Michael (IG@affinityadventure) for the edits.

66GDhfaFZ7s.title: They Sell Tea to Travel the World
66GDhfaFZ7s.description:
Text me! +1 310 349 3854

Today in Kochi, I came across a regular tea shop to get some Indian chai (my favorite drink here!)

The tea shop, Sree Balaji, is owned by a lovely couple in 70s -- Vijayan and Mohana.  After speaking with them for about 30 minutes, I was in awe by their inspiring life story.  

Vijayan and his wife both shared a common dream to travel the world, but money was always an issue.  So 55 years ago, Vijayan took up selling tea on the streets of Kochi.

They saved 300 Rupees ($4.20) every day for decades, and they used this income (together with bank loans) to fund travels to 23 countries!   From Switzerland to Brazil to the USA, and they don't plan on stopping anytime soon.

Vijayan and Mohana are a perfect couple who is living the happiest life that anyone can live.  I am so happy that I dropped by their tea shop today, and I wish them the best of luck in their future travels!

U7R9at_TBa8.title: Be Thankful For Your Parents
U7R9at_TBa8.description:
Dear Mom and Dad,

I love you guys more than anything in the world, and I will never be able to thank you enough for all you've done for me.  

You both have sacrificed a huge part of your life to give me opportunity to play competitive sports, attend a great college, study abroad (etc) — and you've always supported my decision to travel the world and making a living online.

It's been an amazing past 2.5 weeks with you guys in Hong Kong, Macau, Bali, Phuket and Bangkok!   We've had so many fun memories that we will cherish forever, and I can't wait to see you again in a few months. 

To everyone else reading this, please take a moment to call your parents and/or loved ones today and say hi.  If anything, it will mean more to them than it will to you.

Instagram @drewbinsky -- I'm about to kick off 2019 with a bang! See you in India 🇮🇳🇮🇳🇮🇳

9hplxo0j5bY.title: Giving Massages for 40 Years for $25/day
9hplxo0j5bY.description:
While sitting on the beach today in Phuket, we were approached by a lovely lady named Mona Lisa.  She offered to give me (and my parents) a massage, which we easily agreed because of her kindness and warming personality. 

Not only was her massage one of the best I've ever had, but her story is so eye opening that I decided to make this impromptu video.   

She has been working for 10 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year on this exact beach since 1979, while raising 5 children.  The kicker? She makes an average of $25 USD per day. 

Meeting people like Mona Lisa is always a reality check for me to appreciate the life that I live, because I am lucky.  And if you are reading this right now, then you are also lucky because you have a computer and/or phone and internet access. 

All too often, we take these things in our lives for granted.  

Instagram @drewbinsky 

PS-- This video was entirely shot on my iPhone 10XS and Osmo Pocket.  It's the first time in 520+ videos that I didn't use my GH5 and mic.  Personally, I think the quality of the footage isn't so bad, but the audio needed help.  Would love to get your feedback on it!

hXSImqV5Ios.title: How British Are THE FALKLAND ISLANDS?
hXSImqV5Ios.description:
https://www.instagram.com/drewbinsky

Red Telephone Booths? English Speaking? Fish 'n Chips?

That's the Falkland Islands (Islas Malvinas) in a nutshell -- THEY ARE SHOCKINGLY BRITISH, more so than anywhere I've been in Great Britain. I cannot tell you how bizarre it is to be 8,000 miles away from the U.K., and feel this strong of a British influence in the small archipelago called the Falkland Islands.

As many of you may know, the history of the Falkland Islands is complicated and bloody... The sovereignty of the islands is part of an ongoing dispute between the U.K. and nearby Argentina, as it was fought out over a brutal 10-week war in 1982, which ultimately led to Argentina surrendering. The conflict still exists today, more than you might imagine.

I made this video to teach you a little about the history of the Falkland Islands, as well as show you some things I've discovered and learned over the last 3 days I spent here with Hurtigruten. Have I mentioned that the nature and wildlife in the Falkland Islands is breathtaking?!

Just out of curiosity -- did you already know about the British influence of the Falkland Islands? Or is this all news to you?

sPsbVtQbJx0.description:
TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

The last 48 hours inside of this magical 7 star hotel has felt like a dream... Can someone pinch me right now, or is this real life?

Georgia is truly an amazing country all around -- from the food to the hospitality to the nature...  But you'd never expect there to be one of the most epic 7 star hotels in the world, right?!  

Paragraph, a 7 star hotel nesting along the Georgian Black Sea, is one of the coolest accommodation experiences I've ever had, and the best part is that it's very affordable.  You can get a room for under $100USD in winter season (i.e. now), which is about 15-20X cheaper than an equivalent resort in the U.S.  Seriously!

tl1GAWlj2YM.title: What It's Like Being White in Africa...
tl1GAWlj2YM.description:
In 2018, I've had the pleasure of visiting 21 countries in sub-Saharan Africa.  I absolutely love this continent.  It offers incredible nature, culture and experiences that you cannot find anywhere else.  

In a sense, I feel like traveling Africa is the only "real" traveling that I've ever done.

That all being said, I cannot ignore the fact that I am treated differently because of my skin color.  

I have noticed a lot more scamming and bribery happening to me in African countries than anywhere else.   Some of the scariest travel situations I've been in happened to me here, and thus, I need to take extra caution of every decision I make.  

I know this post will get a lot of hate mail, and that's okay.  I want to hear your opinions, thoughts and suggestions on this subject.

I could lie to you guys and say that Africa is 100% safe as a non-black person, but that's just not the case.  Perhaps it would be safer if I didn't travel solo, but I always have. 

I have felt racism in Africa the same way that black people feel racism in the U.S., or Asians in Europe, or Hispanics in Australia.   The point of this video is that if you physically stand out in any place, you will be treated differently.  And I wish someday, in this amazing world of ours, that this will not be the case.

K_R2Q9sYSfY.title: Thoughts on IRAN After 6 Months...
K_R2Q9sYSfY.description:
Iran touched my heart in more ways than I ever imagined.

6 months ago I was on a 2 week journey around Iran, and not a day goes by where I don't think about the fun times I had in Iran.

In my mind, Iran is still the most misunderstood country in the world. It has THE MOST humble & hospitable people, delicious foods, ancient history and a culture that feels like you've traveled back in time.

And should I mention that Iran is one of the world's safest countries? I felt safer traveling in Iran than I do in my own country -- this is not a joke.

And just in case you are wondering — nobody told me to make this video. It is not sponsored. I made it out of pure joy because I want to share with you my 100% honest thoughts and feelings towards Iran. I can't wait to visit again soon (hopefully 2019!)

Have you ever been to Iran? Do you agree that it's the most misunderstood country in the world?

JRnkTFDuYqk.title: The Simple Life!
JRnkTFDuYqk.description:
The last 24 hours have been so simple.   The 14 of us arrived in Ban Sam Kha -- a tiny Northern Thai village of 170 families, tucked away in the mountains and nestled in between luscious rice fields.

It was the simplest day I've spent in a long time.  

When we arrived, we were welcomed into the village in a lovely Buddhist ceremony then invited for some home cooked dinner.  The following morning, we caught sunrise in the rice fields and learned how to harvest rice (it's harvesting season now!).  To wrap it up, we spent some time with kids in the school and they taught us how to weave Buddhist flags.

It feels like life moves in slow motion here.  Nobody is rushing to get anywhere.  And everyone is always smiling!  This place is a true paradise. 

Sometimes when I spend too much time in cities, I forget how relaxing it is in the countryside (anywhere in the world).  It's like hitting the "reset button" on life.  I recommend taking a day trip to some small village sometime soon.  You will thank me later!

Instagram @drewbinsky.  Thanks Michael for the edits (IG: @affinityadventure) and Mitch Summers for the drone shots.

jAyhw6lOyAk.title: Most Unique Tribe in Asia? (LONG NECKS)
jAyhw6lOyAk.description:
TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854 

I have finally met with the LONG NECK tribe of Northern Thailand - and they are truly some of the most fascinating humans on earth! 

As you probably know, my favorite thing to do when traveling is to discover and interact with the most local people I can find. To eat their food, observe their homes and experience first-hand how they survive. 

I’ve spent quality time with the Himba tribe of Namibia, the Mursi tribe of Ethiopia and the Huli tribe of Papua New Guinea. But never have I seen women wearing dozens of heavy metal rings around their neck... until I came to Northern Thailand!! 

They wear the rings (traditionally) to protect from tiger bites, but also to differentiate from the other hi tribes of Myanmar/Thailand.. and of course, it’s also a beauty/fashion thing!

The long necks are actually refugees from Myanmar who crossed the border in the 18th century and never returned back home. There are some 40,000 of them remaining today, mostly up in the mountains near the Burma border. 

Have you ever heard about the long neck tribe? What do you think about their culture? Comment below! 

TEXT ME +1 310 349 3854 and I will respond :)

Ut5R-GAiEuE.title: Ice Cream of the Future? (Thai Ice Cream Rolls)
Ut5R-GAiEuE.description:
Any ice cream lovers out there?  Please allow me to introduce you to one of Thailand's greatest inventions... THAI ICE CREAM ROLLS!

They are exactly what they sound like -- little rolls of flavored ice cream, about the diameter of a quarter, packed into a cup and topped with all sorts of delicious toppings like hot fudge, coconut shavings, toasted marshmallow, fresh fruit and/or gummy bears.

Thai Ice Cream Rolls are way better than they sound in words.  Trust me. 

I've been wanting to make a video about ice cream rolls since I moved to Thailand in June -- so here it is and I hope you enjoy :)

Share this video if you've tried (or want to try) Thai ice cream rolls!

Instagram: @drewbinsky   

Special thanks to Michael (IG @affinityadventure) for the intro sequence.  Music: Epidemic Sound

FzjtCj36AJI.title: The Man That Rescues Dogs (Thailand's Soi Dogs)
FzjtCj36AJI.description:
Sadly, Thailand has more than 2 million street dogs.  These dogs are ownerless, abandoned and most of them are starving, skinny and sick, covered with scabs or fleas.  It's a horrible situation that has gained little attention from the outside world -- until a Swedish man named Michael came to town.

I had the great pleasure of meeting Michael today (AKA The man that rescues dogs) at his home/dog warehouse in rural Thailand.  I was fascinated to hear his story of how he has (literally) rescued thousands of dogs off the streets and given them food, shelter and health care.

Join me today as I introduce you into Michael's life -- a life which has been entirely devoted to saving dogs.  It doesn't get any more inspiring than this...  Thoughts?

Special thanks to Michael for the edits (IG: @affinityadventure)

LuSFJOqheEg.title: HE DOES EVERYTHING!
LuSFJOqheEg.description:
Patrick is one of the coolest and nicest guys I’ve met in all my travels. He's the definition of an entrepreneur, a workaholic and a hustler. He really does everything!

When he saw that I was coming to Gabon, he immediately reached out on Facebook and offered to show me around his hometown of Libreville. Not only did he pick me up at the airport, give me a room in his house to crash at and take me all over his town of Libreville, Gabon — but he wouldn’t let me spend a dime. 

I tried and tried and tried to pay for food, gas, etc, but he wouldn’t let me. What did he expect in return? Absolutely nothing.

localized.title: HE DOES EVERYTHING!
localized.description:
Patrick is one of the coolest and nicest guys I’ve met in all my travels. He's the definition of an entrepreneur, a workaholic and a hustler. He really does everything!

When he saw that I was coming to Gabon, he immediately reached out on Facebook and offered to show me around his hometown of Libreville. Not only did he pick me up at the airport, give me a room in his house to crash at and take me all over his town of Libreville, Gabon — but he wouldn’t let me spend a dime. 

I tried and tried and tried to pay for food, gas, etc, but he wouldn’t let me. What did he expect in return? Absolutely nothing.

It’s people like Patrick who make me really appreciate the people all over the world. He will be in all of my upcoming Gabon videos so stay tuned!

IXxNnduTtXw.title: 5 Best Things About NAMIBIA
IXxNnduTtXw.description:
An incredible 10 day journey around Namibia has finally come an end.  I am so sad to leave Namibia beacuse it truly is one of the most magnificent places on earth.  Who knew Namibia would be such a gem in the southern part of Africa?  From now on, I only have amazing things to say about Namibia! 

From the stunning nature to the humbling people and everything in between -- I will 100% be back to Namibia again soon, and I can't wait! 

This video explains my 5 favorite things about Namibia. If you have any further questions, please comment them and I'll get back to you.

mPAb8qXM0Ws.title: This Guy is SO IMPRESSIVE | Clicking Language
mPAb8qXM0Ws.description:
Today, somewhere in the Namibian desert, I met an impressive guy named Frans. His native dialect is the clicking language!

He was born and raised in this dry, windy climate of stunning red sand dunes and wild-roaming zebras. And leopards. And wildebeests. And snakes. 

I was so impressed by Frans's desert survival skills and knowledge of 11 (ELEVEN) languages fluently -- including his native dialect of the 'clicking language' -- so it was impossible for me not to share his story with you.

One of the biggest motivators for me to continue my journey to every country in the world is meeting unique people and getting a glimpse into their daily lives. Frans is a perfect example of this. 

Music: Ben Sound

ajWdUvmolag.title: I FOUND MARS ON EARTH (NAMIBIA)
ajWdUvmolag.description:
I have never been to Mars, but I imagine that it would look very similar to what I have seen today in Namibia. 

Seriously guys! I am still in shock by what I have just experienced in the world's oldest desert, dating back 80 million years... But that's not even the coolest part. 

Namibia's desert is home to the largest and tallest SAND DUNES on earth -- reaching up to 1,200 feet high. I spent all day trekking around these dunes and I am left speechless. 

HAVE YOU EVER BEEN TO NAMIBIA? If not, then add it to your list!

kjOH_4NEcAY.title: Namibia is... GERMAN?!
kjOH_4NEcAY.description:
Yesterday, I arrived in Namibia (my 143rd country!) to start a 10 day tour with G Adventures! But as I've been wandering around the unique capital city of Windhoek, I couldn't help but notice how GERMAN everything feels. Seriously, the culture is bizarre here in Namibia! 

As I investigated further, I discovered that Namibia was a German colony (from 1884 - 1915), and despite 103 years of separation since the Germans left, their influence is still deeply rooted in Namibian society today.

I became so fascinated by this German-Namibian culture, because the vast majority of the world that I've seen has been conquered by either the British, French, Spanish, Portuguese or Dutch... Not the Germans. 

Here is a fun video I put together today all about my observations on German-influenced Namibia. 

Just out of curiosity -- Is this all news to you? Or did you know that Namibia is German-influenced?

h8Be3AA11mE.description:
TOMORROW, I'm leaving for a massive trip around Central and West Africa to 9 countries -- Namibia, Angola, São Tomé and Príncipe, Equatorial Guinea, Cameroon, Gabon, Chad, Mali & Mauritania.

This trip to Africa has been VERY challenging to plan, tedious to get visas for (5 countries), and extremely expensive to book flights & hotels ($15K+ out of pocket) -- but it's going to be a trip of a lifetime and I CAN'T WAIT to show you places that you've probably never heard of before. 

Safety is my biggest concern on this trip, as most of these countries aren't built for tourism and I am going in with all of my camera gear, etc -- so I decided to make this video, which explains 3 ways I am keeping myself safe! 

Are you ready to see brand new content from Central/West Africa? Here we gooooooooooo!

V6jjbxgvQqA.title: LA vs. NYC: Which is Better?
V6jjbxgvQqA.description:
It's great to be back in Los Angeles, California! I'm here for a long layover -- visiting friends, and applying for a 6-month multiple entry visa to Thailand (fingers crossed I get it!)

Anyways, L.A. is the second biggest city in the U.S. and it represents the entire West Coast. Whenever I'm here, I cannot help but compare it to America's biggest city, New York, which represents the East Coast. 

While both LA & NYC are big, cosmopolitan and diverse -- they are different in just about every way possible. Find out why in this video.

I'd love to get your thoughts - Which do you enjoy better - LA or NYC? Do you agree or disagree with my points?  Comment below!

aYtUlm73uTw.title: My First 24 Hours in MADAGASCAR
aYtUlm73uTw.description:
What a whirlwind the past 24 hours of my life have been in Madagascar!!

I decided to come to Madagascar with absolutely no plan. It's fun being spontaneous sometimes. 

I arrived in the capital of Madagascar called Antananarivo early this morning with no hotel reservation, no plan and no idea what I'd be doing... Just seeking adventure!

Through Facebook, I got in touch with a local girl named Ali, who picked me up at the airport with her 2 classmate friends, Dave and Nancy. Not only have they been AMAZING tour guides around Antananarivo, but Dave volunteered to let me sleep at his house with his family -- who cooked me a delicious dinner of Madagascar food called Vary Amin’anana. Life doesn't get any better than this!

Today is a day that I'll never forget. I am so happy to be back in Africa and so thankful to be able to find people like Ali, Dave & Nancy from social media. I can't wait to see more of Madagascar over the coming days!

qaL3t--PsTI.title: This Thai City Has Transformed! (Pattaya)
qaL3t--PsTI.description:
I finally made the 2 hour journey South East of Bangkok to the coastal Thai city of Pattaya!

I've heard a lot of things about Pattaya over the years, and it has almost exclusively been negative... such as a destination only for sex tourism, filled with old single men. 

While this reputation about Pattaya may be true to an extent, I was shocked to discover a completely different Pattaya than what I had imagined. The city has essentially had a facelift -- transforming into a family friendly place with dozens of attractions, amusement parks, botanical gardens and world class shopping malls. Wait until you see what else we discovered in Pattaya!

Thank you to my friend Dan about Thailand (who has been living in Pattaya for 12 years) for taking me all over Pattaya to make this video. We had a blast! Check out his vlogs as well.

SQH2eDn41xY.title: The Land of the LADYBOY
SQH2eDn41xY.description:
TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854 

This is a video I've been wanting to make since I moved to Thailand. It's all about the ladyboy culture in Thailand. 

Ladyboys, or transgenders, are extremely common in Thailand and you will see them everywhere — on the streets, on the metro, in restaurants and especially in nightlife areas. Many times, you won't even notice it's a ladyboy, since they look like beautiful women.

The reason I made this video is to A) educate you about the ladyboy culture in Thailand and B) tell you how accepting Thailand is to treat them like normal members of society. It's remarkable.

As you and I both know, dozens and dozens of countries in today's world are moving in the opposite direction towards acceptance of those in the LGBTQ community — so this video can be a lesson to the world. 

They are just people — let them live their lives. 

What are you thoughts on ladyboys? Would love to get your opinions. Thank you

TEXT ME +1 310 349 3854 and I will respond :) 

Do you want exclusive travel advice, need help planning a trip or want a personalized shoutout? Request a custom video from me on CAMEO: https://www.cameo.com/drewbinsky

P.S... P.S. - I apologize for my hoarse voice — I picked up some infection and it went straight to my throat!

d-k99Mbcb5I.title: From Food Lover to Role Model... Meet Mr. Big
d-k99Mbcb5I.description:
This 5 minute video highlights the story of an amazing man, Mr. Big, who I've spent the last 3 days with eating & traveling around Thailand.

He's one of the most incredible and inspiring people I've ever met. 

Mr. Big, a native of Bangkok, quit his job 10 years ago as a real estate mogul to pursue his dream in the food business -- because he LOVES EATING more than anyone else I've met. 

Not only has he found success over the last few years -- in the form of a popular Thai TV show and opening up KRBB butchery in Bangkok serving the finest cuts of Japanese & Thai beef -- but he prioritizes in giving back to young farmers in the province to help them grow. 

Mr. Big, unexpectedly, invited Deanna and I to northern Thai province of Nan to get a new experience of Thailand and see where he sources his pigs (he covered all our expenses and wouldn't let us pay for anything).

While in Nan, we met some of the young farmers that he supports by giving them opportunities to succeed, such as taking them on trips to Japan to learn from the masters themselves. Mr. Big is the definition of a role model to these kids. 

Also - Mr. Big kept repeating his philosophy in life, which is to keep giving back, and in the long run, you will eventually get back in return. He doesn't care about money. He geniunely wants to see others succeed. 

These are only the bullet points of Mr. Big's story -- I encourage you to learn the rest in this video, that I am very proud of!

localized.title: From Food Lover to Role Model... Meet Mr. Big
localized.description:
This 5 minute video highlights the story of an amazing man, Mr. Big, who I've spent the last 3 days with eating & traveling around Thailand.

He's one of the most incredible and inspiring people I've ever met. 

Mr. Big, a native of Bangkok, quit his job 10 years ago as a real estate mogul to pursue his dream in the food business -- because he LOVES EATING more than anyone else I've met. 

Not only has he found success over the last few years -- in the form of a popular Thai TV show and opening up KRBB butchery in Bangkok serving the finest cuts of Japanese & Thai beef -- but he prioritizes in giving back to young farmers in the province to help them grow. 

Mr. Big, unexpectedly, invited Deanna and I to northern Thai province of Nan to get a new experience of Thailand and see where he sources his pigs (he covered all our expenses and wouldn't let us pay for anything).

While in Nan, we met some of the young farmers that he supports by giving them opportunities to succeed, such as taking them on trips to Japan to learn from the masters themselves. Mr. Big is the definition of a role model to these kids. 

Also - Mr. Big kept repeating his philosophy in life, which is to keep giving back, and in the long run, you will eventually get back in return. He doesn't care about money. He geniunely wants to see others succeed. 

These are only the bullet points of Mr. Big's story -- I encourage you to learn the rest in this video, that I am very proud of!

sP7TQvNuz6I.title: How Diverse is MALAYSIA?!
sP7TQvNuz6I.description:
HELLO MALAYSIA! 

I am beyond excited to be back here for a third visit! Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia is a LOT different than I remembered it back in 2014 (when I was here as budget backpacker...) It's bizarre to see how much a city can evolve in just 4 years.

Anyways, the thing I love most about this fascinating country of Malaysia (along with the food) is the extreme DIVERSITY of its citizens. Just walk down any street in K.L., and you'll see all different faces in every different color, with each person uniquely identifying themselves as Malaysian. I say "uniquely" because no two people in this country have the same blood - it's all mixed (mostly with some combination of ethnic Malay, Chinese, and/or Indian!)

This video will explain a little bit more about Malaysia’s spectacular diversity. 

Stay tuned over the next 3 days as I rediscover Kuala Lumpur's lifestyle, sites, cuisine and people -- I can't wait to show you what's next! And THANK YOU to everyone who came to my meet up. That was amazing. 

Have you ever been to Malaysia?

NcVkDNs3Bp4.title: This Band's Concept is AMAZING!
NcVkDNs3Bp4.description:
Remember the burger guy, Taiki, who I featured last week? Well, I'm so glad I met him because he introduced me to his musical friends who run the famous band and YouTube channel Madpuppet Studio.

Madpuppet Studio began back in 2012, when 3 high school friends named Jane, Oat and Nut made a cover song and put it on YouTube. Fast forward 6 years, and now they are the most famous cover band & production team in Thailand with hundreds of millions of video views.

BUT the story doesn't end there. Wait until you hear about the band's amazing concept!

Instead of being selfish and 'shining in the spotlight' -- the 3 original band members have decided to provide opportunities to other young musicians who want to play with them. So each new music video they record for their YouTube Channel features other talented musicians that they have recruited. 

I joined their studio recording yesterday and was completely amazed by what I saw. Not to mention, every single one of them is EXTREMELY talented and gifted, and their video/audio production is the best I've ever seen in my life. 

For more of their videos, head over to their YouTube channel - https://www.youtube.com/user/Madpuppetstudio

J_6p64ji7WE.title: She's From... Everywhere?! (Third Culture Kid)
J_6p64ji7WE.description:
TEXT ME! +1 310 349 3854

I met Pixie last week at a community builder event in Bangkok. When I asked her where she's from, she told me:

"I'm from Hungary."

Then, we spoke for a few minutes and I realized that she isn't from Hungary. That's only what her passport says. She's from the U.S./Canada/China/Malaysia and she speaks 5 languages fluently; none of them are Hungarian.

Are you confused yet? This video will give you a glimpse of Pixies identity!!

Are there any other 'Third Culture Kids' out there who can relate to Pixie (people raised in a culture other than their parents' or the country on their passport?) Please let us know your story below!

RRTaulIp160.title: Why I HATE Politics...
RRTaulIp160.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

I couldn't wait any longer to make this video.

I hate politics. With a burning passion. This is something that I haven't discussed much, but I feel very passionate about. 

In my eyes, politics = negativity, turmoil & greed. Nearly all politicians in this world are obsessed with 2 things: money and power, and I've witnessed and/or heard stories about this happening in each of the 140 countries I have visited.

Sure, politics is important for putting necessary laws in place, for assuring people can live safely in their country and for understanding how the world works... But I don't understand why it always has to revolve around negativity when there is SO MUCH MORE POSITIVITY happening around us!

I guess what I am trying to say is that I am a very positive and optimistic person, and politics is exactly the opposite -- so I choose not to involve myself in politics in any way, shape or form.

I'd love to get your thoughts and opinions about this - do you also remove yourself from politics? Or are you one of those people who can't get enough?

📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

Bhutan is one of the most expensive countries in the world to visit, charging a tax (or fee) of $250 per person PER DAY.  No way around it, unless you hold an Indian passport where you are exempt from these fees.  Yes, Bhutan is expensive, but yes, Bhutan is worth it (trust me!)

WHY DO THEY CHARGE $250 PER PERSON PER DAY?

In this video, I explain the reasoning behind why the Bhutanese government charges such a hefty fee, and why I strongly believe that it's worth spending the money to visit!

Have you ever been to Bhutan? Are you planning to go? Stay tuned for tomorrow, as we're going to hike up to the famous Tiger's Nest!

SZMPmFEgYIA.title: No TV Until 1999? (Seriously)
SZMPmFEgYIA.description:
📲 My JUST GO APP is here! Connect w/ travelers for free: https://apple.co/3vYPr75 
✅ SUBSCRIBE for more travel videos: https://bit.ly/3iAZlnw

Could you imagine growing up, 20 years ago, without having TV or the internet?!

In Bhutan, they didn't introduce TV or the internet to its citizens until the year 1999 -- making them the world's last country to do so.

While that may seem like torture to many people reading this, the Bhutanese see it in the opposite way. 

They simply don't want to be a victim of modernization. They are afraid of globalization. They are happy with their traditional way of life that has been practiced for centuries and centuries. 

And as a result, they are ranked one of the happiest and greenest countries in the world. Anyone else see a pattern here?!
